I brought the question to stimulate discussion, and am 'on the fence' with it.  I agree with your point about his appreciation of documentary, and his improvisatory flair that occasionally comes to the fore.  I think, when you boil it all down, he was a GOOD composer.  That is, always taking chances, goin with instincts, etc, in order to make his idea as sincere.. maybe that's the wrong word.. as lucid as possible. (?)
I think he is successful at times (70%?) and at time not.  
And example of successful would be the sequence you mention below from Solaris.  I'm beginning to explore electro-acoustic music as a composer, and find his use of sound here to be very simple and musical.  I would argue that role Gestalt 
theory plays here, and would encourage everyone to listen to the sounds leading up to this point:
From the get go, nature sounds are at the fore, and stick to their respective scenes; that is, those in which they were actually recorded.  Slowly there builds a smearing of the time element: We hear the water in the fore even as Chris goes inside (also a little foreshadowing? maybe too subtle.. ) the house.  This process is explored, not entirely smoothly, up until what I think of as the crescendo, when (I forget his name) returns to the city.


>Also the long takes alert us that we are waiting for something. If there is
>no reason to cut away then our attention is heightened with expectation,
>given that we trust him, that is. Whether or not this satisfies is
>determined by the imagination of the audience. Now you might say that this
>is cheap mystification, or you might say that it is a chance to practice
>your Zazen. There's enough evidence for me to believe that Tark does
>include meanings, small gestures that do spark our imagination, signs and,
>yes, even symbols. (Others on the list may disagree, indeed the enigmatic
>character of T's work is very important to me as well. Somehow I find a way
>to have my take and eat it too.) 

I wonder about this 'suspense' element, if we can call it that, in his pacing.  It's interesting because I hadn't thought about it, but I think this is what lies at the core of my problem with his pacing: the intention is muddled.  It's not a completely clear signal.  Mind you, I'm not against this, and will watch repeatedly the scene a bit after the bombs/planes fly overhead in Sacrifice, in which the Wife writhes bawling on the floor and switches languages every other line.  I'll watch it until I understand it, like I've listened to things umpteen times until I understand them.
I have qualms about depending on this from the audience, though.  This is getting a bit tangential, so...

