Hi,
	
	I agree with both of your comments in regards to T's vocab vs Hollywood's vocab.  I think it goes beyond that a bit, not much, but a bit.
Do you think if I was raised in India, North Africa, or Eastern Europe that I would have an easier time with the pacing?  I mention these countries because they are farther from Hollywood's grasp.  I think it's an interesting question, and one I'd like your input on.  I don't actively compare anything in T's work to Hollywood, of course, and doubt if I do so on much of a subliminal level anymore.  I had to drop any conventional models for music awhile ago, and think the same applies for film.  I don't think it's fair to assume everyone raised in America sees film through a Hollywood consciousness, do you?

Another important issue in regard to pacing is the relationship between the theater viewing and the video viewing.  I, for one, have only seen Solaris in a theater, and the rest on video.  The pacing is much easier to absorb in the theater, I think, because the image at the intended size is much easier to get lost in.  

PS I didn't point it out but I think this was very well said:
"The tendency for the uninflected shot (one shot = one message) means that
The shot in itself contains very little meaning, and we automatically
search for the edit point to glean information. It also stylises the
representation of reality on screen to a series of meaningful looks and
gestures to convey thought and emotion. It discards what is believed to be
extraneous time and space. But for what Tarkovsky tries to convey, the long
shot is the right 'tool'."







