But seriously, 
I don't know that T's 'moves' ie the speed he take sequences are consistent enough to call them this.  Legato could be interpreted as a sequence of shorter sections of film uniting as a "phrase", or you could apply it more 'microscopically, to mean said sequence consisting of overlapping, maybe cross-fading small sections..  Anyone else?  Those musical terms you mentioned, at least to this kid, have VERY classical overtones, which may/may not be appropriate to the film in question.  I prefer 'fast' 'slow' 'ragged' 'panting' etc. in other words, plain english.  

I think the "value" involved in using musical annotations would be to the person annotating.  You would organize your thoughts on the piece with such a technique. In such a case, who cares if it's of value to anyone else, go for it!



