Hey Pavel!


I'm very happy to get your perspective. I suspected that such customs
were normal. (Still, the anecdote about B kissing T in public and
causing people to stare does seem peculiar) Anyway as I've said before,
I wonder why Johnson and Petrie make the assertion in their book that
Russia is extremely homophobic? Suggesting that we in the West are less
so?


<paraindent><param>right,left</param><italic>Visual Fugue</italic> P
17: "His bisexuality remains a well hidden secret in the extremely
homophobic Russian Society."


Also:<italic> Visual Fugue</italic> P 248: "While most of the other
facts of his private life were well known to insiders, his apparent
bisexuality is only now being quietly discussed. Was this the "deep,
dark evil" that tormented him (Rerberg interview), that he could not
share with anyone in the extremely homophobic Soviet society?

</paraindent>

I quote these not as evidence of T's sexual behaviour but because of
the references to Soviet and Russian homophobia. Of course I don't
trust everything I read in their book (or anyone else's) and it's
easily conceivable to me that the subject is ill conceived.


Yes I've read a bit, watched some films, followed the careers of a few
Russian artists, hell I even subscribed to "Soviet Life" for years and
I still don't know anything, that's why I said in an earlier post that
I <italic>thought</italic> it was common for men to be more
affectionate to one another, much more than we are here in the States.
Thanks again for verifying this, personally.


It's led me to wonder if we humans feel more free to show affection
when there is some assurance that our love will not be taken as
something sexual? Such configurations of taboos and customs may serve
to actually allow us to feel closer to one another without the
relationship becoming intimate. Providing a society with more
affectionate behavior could not be a bad idea, to show our love for one
another as a part of our custom... it remains social not personal.


In this respect I think the term "homophobic" is decidedly prejudiced.
But perhaps it's difficult to ingrain such definitive lines in our
behavior without fear and anxiety that we find associated with the term
"Taboo". 


But I think these social conventions are in a way a kind of heightened
respect for privacy. Here in the US our sense of privacy has been
completely exploited, mostly I think by Television. We all have a sense
that we live in one another's homes. If there is no respectable sense
of privacy then everything personal about us has no where to belong,
its nothing short of apocalyptic.  And this aspect is something T was
very concerned with in his later films.


Not sure what you mean by "boulevard shit" but I like it. What is
"boulevard shit"? The place where people walk their house pets? A
gathering place on the street where losers hang out to gab and try and
impress one another? Is it a Russian colloquialism? I've never heard it
but whatever it means I like the phrase. As soon as I finish my PHD in
pedantry*, I'm there, thats where I'll be.



>> tragic transformation of B's personality under pressure of his parts
in

>> T's films. As a small boy he was playing spy, which had one concrete
enemy

>> and aim. His will was directed to DESTROY that enemy. Then, Boriska
in AR:

>> one against the world, everyone is enemy. T's gipnosis made the
actor B.

>> to be the chracter he played. At the end it leaded Burlyaev to the
darkest

>> forms of human being. Now here in Russia, he is one of the nazi --

>> faschist leaders, antisemith and so on.


First, I spread rumors that Tarkovsky was a fag, now you say he was
hypnotizing people into becoming Fascists?  Boy we ought to get some
good replys to this. Hope we don't get kicked off the list and miss the
fireworks.


Seriously, this is amazing news and I think you have a very valid
point. For one thing, I can see it as an example of what I was talking
about before: what happens when the distinction between one's public
behavior overwhelms the very precarious private identity. Also,
appropriate to what you've described about B's tropism it occurs to me
that B's become a negative of Roublev: where Roublev was conditioned by
the oppressions into a sublime artist, B is conditioned by the sublime
to become an oppressor. Very Tarkovskian. (viz. Domenico)


One last note: It's not my intention to talk about T's sexuality, I
hope our discussion is about issues of identity, psychology and the
experiences of life in, out and around nature's body. The incarnation,
if you will.


There are timeless traditions... mythic, heroic, and esoteric which
involve sexual transgressions, transmigrations and transformations for
important reasons. These have little to do with the mentality of
gossip. I am convinced as you are by the content of the films that T
was not interested in the sexual act per se, but was deeply affected by
the problem of being a sexualised being. His eyes were indeed on the
sky... but note: he never directed <italic>our </italic>gaze there. He
didn't need to. Even in puddles of mud one can find reflective surfaces
for the earth's counterpart.  


S


*Not to be confused with "pederasty", S'il vous plait.


