<x-rich>

<paraindent><param>right,left</param>>I see that a new translation of
Death in Venice has been recently released. It

>apparently includes passages that were suppressed in earlier editions.
Can

>anyone speak to the quality of this new translation? Just curious.

>

>Tarden 

</paraindent>

Hey Tarden


Good to hear from you. The Mann book sounds like news. Do you have any
specifics... publisher, ISBN, editor? I'd like to look at it if I get
time.


By the way, I ran across an idea the other day that might be of
interest to both you and Thomas B.


I was looking into Milton and found that he orchestrates
<italic>Paradise Lost</italic> so that it ends in privacy rather than
in some external or public manner. And then, of course, I thought of
Tarkovsky.


As the story goes, Satan is doing all he can to bring about the
corruption of God's creation and when he succeeds at the end it is very
simply played out between a man and a woman ...in private they are
tempted and they commit the tiny deed. Very small and insignificant.
They take, hand in hand, to "their solitary way".


Thomas did an interpretation of <italic>Nastolghia</italic> some months
back wherein he suggested that the candle scene at the end was a kind
of "harrowing of hell" and it's a thought that has stuck with me. I
think it connects with this schematic of Milton's. 


Gorchakov's action is diametrically opposed to Domenico's public act.
I've always liked the fact that G is not a man of "faith" yet he
performs his faithful duty with an acute since of it's absurdity. His
little routine in the pool has no oratory, no explanation. He makes no
attempt to justify it. He clearly looks embarrassed in front of the few
people that we see nearby him as he strolls to and fro through the
pool. 


I'll keep it short (!) here and finish by saying Milton's account of
the fall seems related because Domenico told G that if he carried the
candle into the pool it would mean the salvation of everyone.


So my list of texts I find contiguous to <italic>Nastolghia</italic>
continues to grow!


<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>Say first, for heav'n
hides nothing from thy view,

Nor the deep tract of hell; say first, what cause

Moved our grand parents in that happy state,

Favoured of heav'n so highly, to fall off


</paraindent>The original broken home....


S  

