Hey Pavel, thanks for being lucid about this topic. 


By the way, I just have to say I have very high esteem for Parajonov's
work. Have you seen the documentary made just before he died? At the
end he accepts an award -- I forget where the festival is -- but
instead of giving an acceptance speech he decides to have a minute of
silence in honor of Tarkovsky who had just died. 

 


The way I understand homophobia is not in terms of violent aggression
but in the mental reflexes, how we jump to conclusions simply for self
defense. I do this myself, thats why I know about it. 


I've been around homosexuality since I was very young, I grew up in the
southern US, in a backward town that was crawling with people who are
not "advanced people". ("Shy People" was filmed near there,
coincidentaly) I too was constantly harassed for looking "like a gurl".
In that atmosphere my mother opened a gay night club when I was in high
school. I was not particularly proud of it, but on the other hand ...I
was sort of proud, you know? 


I had plenty of opportunity to explore my own sexual tendencies. My
very best friend through out high school was gay. Yet around me he
played it straight. My reason for having him as a friend was because he
was intelligent. A perceptive person. He had a very vital mind, which I
find very rare and value greatly, regardless of who they fuck. I speak
of him in the past tense because he died years ago... you can guess
how.


I am certainly capable of being repressed -- as some have suggested
here on the list. I never thought that my friend Carl was gay
throughout the years that we spent together. He told me after we
graduated, and I was surprised. I realize now that I was keeping this
knowledge from myself, to protect myself, to protect our friendship. In
a way it was a kind of tacit agreement -- although he was conscious of
the arrangement and I was not.


This was a very subtle form of homophobia. It was not antagonistic, as
you can see. Still it was an unconscious fear that led me to a slightly
distorted view of reality. I bet I still have a slightly distorted view
of reality. I'm a great deal more self aware now than I was twenty
years ago, but I still find that my mind takes care of things with out
telling me all the details. I think this is normal. 

