Dear subsribers:

I'd like to take a stand and clarify some of the questions. First, a
little bit about myself. I was born and raised in Russia, spent their
the best years of my life. Now I'm living in the U.S. I loved some of
the comments and analysis made by Tony, Scott, and Vladimir about
Tarkovsky and his Films, still a little bit confused though about an
amazing level of devotion expressed by people who don't speak Russian
and know about the culture only from books.
1. Homophobia in Russia. Homosexuals are still opressed and treated with
disrespect. They are publicly humiliated and have been the butts (so to
speak) of jokes for years. However, men do kiss each other. I'm not gay
(not that there's anything wrong with it), but, being under the
influence of alcoholic beverages and being very happy, I've kissed my
buddies in public on numerous occasions. I've also kissed my dad, my
relatives, close friends, and a couple of dogs (just kidding). All my
letters to friends I still end with "Love you". I think it brings people
closer together. 
2. Church. Despite on the communism and despite on constant agression,
Christian Churches have always existed and funcioned. My father is a
scientist and my mother is a psychologist, still I was baptized at my
birth and given a cross that I still have. People have always gone to
churches, the communist allowed most of the churches to function. So,
anyone could've gone to the church on Sunday morning. Although it was
usually done in secrecy and by more common people (communist leaders of
any rank weren't advised to go to the church). Younger generation didn't
believe in God very much, so any one saying that he does could've been
laughed at and wasn't taken seriously. It also meant the end of your
career (in terms of promotions and growth). I can understand the tragedy
