hello everyone, i am new here, but i saw something which you said Greg, 
which i liked, and which reminded me rather of an anecdote someone told 
me last week. You said:

>His films are glowing with love for people, and Christianity, and
>spirituality, and care, and.... just watch them again. Without looking
>at the actors, but looking at the people.

In sydney a tramp had some kind of spiritual awakening and went 
everywhere with a little piece of chalk. He would write, on walls, on 
pavements - anywhere - the word "eternity". People, apparently, would 
see this word, and would stop and think over their whole lives and the 
direction in which civilisation is moving. I discussed the story with my 
friend and we both agreed that the word affected people because of the 
love behind it, the faith behind it. And you see, it is still affecting 
people, because my friend told me that story and now i am writing about 
it.
Tarkovsky only made a few films, but what i like about this website (or 
whatever it is called) is that it takes its cue from that small body of 
work and allows people to express themselves with passion to one 
another, whether it is about films or homosexuality. I heard another 
anecdote recently - an aboriginal man was walking along a street with 
the author of a book i read, and the author was praising the archetects 
of some of sydney's skyscrapers. The aboriginal man suggested that 
perhaps the love or power to create the buildings was present in the 
paper used for the drawings and the bricks used for the building, rather 
than the archetects themselves - who were merely just syphons for what 
was around them. I like the idea that Tarkovsky's films contain so much 
belief and love that any arguments or conversations we have sort of feed 
off it. 
This is perhaps a little bit eccentric though. 

william kremer

