I like this idea, but have to say that I never got this impression. I
distinctly remember seeing one of the women from earlier in the movie in the
crowd at the end. I remember her only because she looks exactly like the
mother of an old friend. Still, there is an odd sense to the villagers in
general--the gossipers in the pool at the beginning is a favorite scene. Just
a bunch of talking heads bobbing around in the water. In a sense they couldbe
stand-ins for the audience in the end, in that they are witnessing the scene
with a good deal more compassion than Domenico's witnesses. After all, unlike
the city folk in Rome, the townspeople actually do run to help Gorchakov.

<<Cinema derives not from painting, literature, sculpture, theater, but
from ancient popular wizardry. It is the contemporary manifestation of
an evolving history of shadows, a delight in pictures that move, a
belief in magic. Its lineage is entwined from the earliest beginning
with Priests and sorcery, a summoning of phantoms. With, at first, only
slight aid of the mirror and fire, men called up dark and secret visits
from regions in the buried mind. In these seances, shades are spirits
which ward off evil.>>

If you like this idea there is a novel by social critic Theodore Roszak called
Flicker that you might enjoy. Via a pretty good conspiracy plot it constructs
an alternate history of cinema that derives it's origins from the Egyptian
priesthood and Knights Templar. Sort of a Foucault's Pendulum of film history.
I wonder if Roszak hadn't read this passage--he must have.

<<It is wrong to assume that art needs the spectator in order to be. The
film runs on without any eyes. The spectator cannot exist without it.
It insures his existence.>>

There is, I think, (as Tallulah Bankhead once quipped) "less to this than
meets the eye." Certainly the spectator cannot be a spectator unless he/she is
seeing something--but that does not negate the fact that film needs spectators
to exist. A chair is not really a chair unless someone exists to sit in it. Or
is it? This is a Platonic take on things, I guess. It is not the individual
function and use of the item, but the ideal item itself that defines it . . .
I.E. A chair is a chair even when there are no bipeds in existence who can sit
in it. Art does not need the spectator in order to BE, but it certainly needs
the spectator in order to be ART. I guess that's the distinction I'd make.
Otherwise it's just celluloid.

<<Metamorphose. An object is cut off from its name, habits, associations.
Detached, it becomes only the thing, in and of itself. When this
disintegration into pure existence is at last achieved, the object is
free to become endlessly anything.>>

More cleverness. The assumption here seems to be that a thing is not in a
state of pure existence if it is bound to labels, uses, etc. Pure existence,
it would seem to me, would be just such bindings and associations. Being, by
which I mean the state of being, is not the ability to become "endlessly
anything"--but the state of being SOMETHING, even several things. Being
anything is, ultimately, the same as being nothing--i.e. not existing at all.
Even the above quote requires "disintegration" for "pure existence" to
occur--a bit of a paradox, no?

As per your occultish response to the idea that Tarkovsky was probably not
directly alluding to MIlton--you raise some interesting points in your
quotation. And I'll certainly concede that Tark may have been influenced by
MIlton's ideas, both directly and indirectly. But I would also point out that
these ideas by no means begin with MIlton who was, himself, dealing with the
Bible and the Classical authors. Which brings us back to the idea that, I
think (hope), I did concede in the first place, namely that Tark and Milton
seemed similar in their thinking. Influence is always a tricky issue--some
allusions are blatant, others subtle, others inadvertent. I think your
connection of Mann's Death in Venice to Nostalghia some time ago (that was
you, wasn't it Scott?) is a good example of either subtle or inadvertent
influence. The presence of religious painting and orthodox ideas (such as
Thomas is one to point out) are usually blatant or subtle. The Milton
connection seems to me at the very least unconscious, if not simply the result
of similar thinking (with, albeit a common basis.)

Phew.

Glad to hear that all this bickering about homo/bi sexuality hasn't been the
sole occupation of the group over last couple of months. And yes, I do
remember how people jump the gun and get all pissed off about some of the
topics.

I'll check up on that Mann for you later today. It looks pretty damned
promising.

Tarden

