<x-rich>Hello Greg


Thanks so much for taking the time to offer your personal point of
view, helping to cultivate the sense of humor in this thread of thought
... while also respecting the seriousness of our intentions.


One striking similarity in your description of Christianity in Russia
sounds very familiar: "Younger generation didn't believe in God very
much, so anyone saying that he does could've been laughed at and wasn't
taken seriously." It seems that adolescent cynicism and hostility
haunts us all.

<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

>  I loved some of

>the comments and analysis made by Tony, Scott, and Vladimir about

>Tarkovsky and his Films, still a little bit confused though about an

>amazing level of devotion expressed by people who don't speak Russian

>and know about the culture only from books.

</paraindent>

So many assertions, opinions and tangents coming from us Americans must
surely feel like a  disregard for Tarkovsky as the cultural hero he is
to many Russians. It's gotta be annoying to more than a few of you. Of
course we do not intend on stealing him away; even still, we (I) should
be more sensitive. I know this is not the main point of your message
but it's a subject I want consider more closely... personally.


It's so easy for us Americans to miss how our preoccupation with T
would come off like a misappropriation. I thank you sincerely for your
graciousness when we transgress and I apologize for my ignorant
<italic>faux pas</italic>.  


Anyway here's a piece I find related in a way. It's an excerpt from a
letter I received a few months ago from a friend who teaches English
Literature. It's an interesting account of a kind of a similar
situaltion. 


<paraindent><param>right,left</param>I went to the Faulkner Conference
back in the summer of 1987, had dinner (fried

chicken and watermelon) on the grounds at Faulkner's house, observed
the pencil

scribblings he had done on the walls of his study; he had the habit of
writing

outlines to his novels there.  Four Russian Faulkner experts gave a
seminar and

were very interesting.  They were from the "Gorky Institute of World
Literature" in Moscow and had been studying English and Faulkner for 20
years and knew more

about Faulkner than the Mississipians who were there.  They talked
about the

parallels between the Russian peasant and the rural Mississippi
characters in

Faulkner's stuff.

</paraindent>

Perhaps none of us are as unique as we feel, subjectively. At any rate,
I wish our dialogues could be free from threat and suspicion, but
that's human nature. Needless to say but saying it anyway, I would be
ludicrous to suggest that any of us Americuns on the list know more
about T than his home boys. The reason I'm here is I enjoy the
exchange, sometimes we make discoveries that are very exciting. Please
don't take the enthusiasm as arrogance or an advance. As for myself I'm
not as convinced as I may often sound. The tone of authority can carry
a voice far but to me it's like a good BM, when it's over we all look
back and wonder where it came from. 


This Faulkner story made me think about my own contradictions. My
immediate response to the image of listening to a bearded professor
full of Stolichnaya*, pontificating about Faulkner's use of the local
Negresses is ... it makes me giggle. 


But I have to admit I would drop everything (except my flask) and be
the first in line (which would be comparatively short in this country).
Most of all, this anectdote is sobering. We all know that Faulkner's
work (as all artists') has a dimension other than the medium - In
Faulkner's case: the written (or spoken) word. It appears from my
friend's point of view that this other dimension is a valid one to him
as well, maybe the most valid of all. 



Now my bit of my auto bio.


I've had an attraction to Russia for as long as I can remember knowing
about the country. I remember taking my mother's copy of <italic>The
Idiot</italic>  off the shelf and staring at the strange cover ... too
young to read it, of course. Now it seems like fate.


I still smile when I remember the very moment, the time and place when
I first read those words..."I am a sick man". It was 18 years ago, I
was sitting on a grassy levee by the beautiful Ouachita river. A region
quite close to Faulkner's, actually, geographically and culturally. But
the moment was memorable <italic>not </italic>because of where I
was,<italic> not</italic> because I had eaten a watermelon, but because
of what I found: <italic>I knew this man</italic>. 


Faulkner I respected outwardly, Dostoyevsky I
<italic>recognized</italic> internally.

 

Five years later I saw a film that was even closer to me. Isn't it
strange that I would tell my wife-to-be that I understood nothing at
all about what I had seen even though I felt a familiarity unlike any
other film? It's two different kinds of knowing, isn't it?


Carl Jung was once asked if he had faith. He smiled and said:
"Faith...? I know ...<italic>I know</italic>." There is quite a lot
about your wonderful country that I will never get around to knowing.
Hell even in my own small world I struggle to understand the simplest
things: math, remote controls, pornography... but one thing I feel very
fortunate to know -just a little- is .... well, me and William's
derelict Aussie: <bold>eternity</bold>. It doesn't take much of it to
make an impression and coming as it does in small and spare doses it's
easy to miss.


Jung spent most of his carreer trying to express what it was that he
<italic>knew</italic>... I think the consensus is: he failed. There are
a few people who are able to communicate something about it...very few.
I'm not one of them. I'm a stranger there so I feel <italic>very
fortunate</italic> when I connect to someone who can show me around.
The culture of Russia is a subject of its own, it's a subject I'm
attracted to, but that <italic>other</italic> country is what it all
comes down to for me. That place where distinctions of language, race
and sex mean <italic>nothing</italic>, that's where I long to spend my
free time. Maybe because I suspect that it's ultimately what I
am...endless <italic>nothing </italic>(or <italic>everything</italic>
as Seamus pointed out)


This is the reason I watch T's films and read about is life, his
interests, his dilemmas and his decisions. His ability to move freely
through Bergman's "rooms" is rare. Yes, he was conditioned by his
setting, for better or worse, as we all are. He never forgot that and
it kept him and his work grounded. To me, knowing his social and
personal circumstances is vitally important to understanding how his
films are balanced. War, family, <italic>Homo Sovieticus</italic>...
all are unspoken constants in his films. 


But its no small point that these are <italic>films.</italic> And his
context in that regard tends, I think, to be more cross cultural. His
medium is the <italic>image</italic>, not the <italic>language</italic>
(that's why he would come up with apparently absurd ideas like filming
an almost silent version of <italic>Hamlet</italic> in John Ford
Valley!) There is, without a doubt, quite a lot of experience conveyed
through his films that I will never have access to due to the obvious
barriers. But for what ever reason there seems to be plenty of
inspiration accessible through <italic>other</italic> portals.


I'm respectfuly jealous that there is a kind of relationship to T that
you guys are born with, one that I will never know. Regardless how
close I feel to him I am not Russian and that's a reality I just don't
want to think about. I can cry and cry and do all I can to make light
of the fact but it remains that you, being Russian, have an
identification with him that is inimitable. 


But I think that I can make a bit of a case in defense of myself and
others, who aren't Russian. There is one aspect of T that outsiders
have that you guys will never be able to experience due to your
familiarity ...and that is a we see a more thorough
<italic>alterity</italic>. 


"Alterity" is strangeness, it's a word that suggests the psychological
stall or even awe that we feel when we encounter something so
different. There might be some fear in this encounter but no
zenophobia. The effect is a kind of beauty, the sublime. I'm thinking
that for us, as forigners, the simplest characteristics of mannerisms
and language in the every day incidentals in T's films -- even as they
are cultural limits -- can be seen as assets, and maybe yet
<italic>another</italic> aesthetic dimension in his films. T's so
natural with his scenes -- yes we can certainly feel that-- but to us
it's all imbued with an even greater strangeness. 


It's a sensability that is appropriate to T's methods, too. He was very
concerned with helping us all see our world with new sense of surprise.
I think this alterity is a considerable subject due to the point that
you made, Greg, that >Tarkovsky, first of all, was a great spiritual
leader and enlightener<<. His choice of sets, his placement and
movement of camera ... he did all kinds of things to increase this
sensation of peculiarity.  Being the kind of artist that he was, I
think he hoped this heightend sense of life's alterity would stay with
us as we left the film and that we might then notice in our own
normalcy something is renewed and unlike our habitual life.


Not to make too big of this alterity thing. I just thought it might
also express something to you about how his films can make such an
impression on us. Perhaps it's a small thing but hey, being overly
proud about small things is part of being a man! 


Anyway, Tarkovsky is the gift that keeps on giving, his multiplicity
has few peers that I have found in world cinema. Which brings me back
to the subject of eternity. But, as you may know, eternity is like a
wild animal. At the same time we hunt for it, eternity is stalking us.
So we move around it... it's too late to run ... to approach it
directly is impossible....  Perhaps because I'm older now I feel the
animal is closing in. I need some trust worthy advice on learning how
to live with it, you know? Tark is one of the few filmmakers I've found
who knows the problem.


So I'm interested in the discussions whether they be about Petric's
oneric style, esoteric gobbledegook or the latest Tarkovsky Laser Disc
and action figures. Some subjects have made me indignant (and
embarrased) in the past. My hope is that I am trying to stay focused on
an aesthetic that invokes a bit of ...you know what. 


I apologise for the leangth of this harangue, and thank you for
listening. Please participate more! I know the English can mean more
work for you guys but I really would like to encourage the exchange.
The artist in me respects the unutterable ---but also works for
understanding. Personlly I would love to read more from your
<italic>Russain </italic>perspective... and <italic>personal</italic>
perspective as well.


Finally (!), I also hope you are able to create a home for yourself
here in the U.S. without too much abrasion and loss.



S




*Theres a technique for eating watermelon in this region of the South
that I can personally account for that may or may not be implied in the
story. 


How to eat a watermelon: carefully cut a hole in the side of the melon
just big enough for the spout of a bottle of Vodka to be inserted.
After the bottle is drained, plug the piece of watermelon back into
place and refrigerate. 


Later, one might take a date for a walk through the cotton fields down
to the banks of the bayou where the fully ripened fruit can be enjoyed
in private, beneath an obscured, mosquito flickering moon. 



</x-rich>
