Excellent point, Scott (I happen to know a Scott Rhodes here in LA and I'm
hoping like hell you're not him because the one I know is something of a
buffoon, albeit a nice guy).  My grandfather told me once that he had always
like Russians because they loved the same three things we Iranians hold most
dear:  tea, our families, and sadness.  The main objection I face when
proselytizing re: Tarkovsky (a practice I've pretty much given up on) is that
he's "too depressing" or that his films are "too sad".  This is something that
always pissed me off.  What kind of objection is that?  It took me a long time
to realize that many cultures don't prize a certain type of suffering the way
Iranian culture does.  It's seen either as a misery to be avoided or a price
to paid for attaining a higher wisdom.  

I've found Russian poetry similar in tone to Farsi and Arabic poetry in this
respect:  suffering is seen sometimes as a beautiful, immediate, forceful sign
that we are alive; and sometimes as a joyful end in itself.  This may sound
like a lot of crap but I'm afraid I can't think of a more coherent way of
explaining it.  Incidentally, for anybody who doesn't care for vodka (I feel
like a traitor!) rum works well also, though it blends better with fleshier
melons like cantaloupe.

Best wishes to all
