Tarden, you replied to Scott:

><<Metamorphose. An object is cut off from its name, habits, associations.
>Detached, it becomes only the thing, in and of itself. When this
>disintegration into pure existence is at last achieved, the object is
>free to become endlessly anything.>>
>
>More cleverness. The assumption here seems to be that a thing is not in a
>state of pure existence if it is bound to labels, uses, etc. Pure existence,
>it would seem to me, would be just such bindings and associations. Being, by
>which I mean the state of being, is not the ability to become "endlessly
>anything"--but the state of being SOMETHING, even several things. Being
>anything is, ultimately, the same as being nothing--i.e. not existing at all.
>Even the above quote requires "disintegration" for "pure existence" to
>occur--a bit of a paradox, no?

Maybe you haven't experienced this, but something like it is available
under certain conditions. Things are as they are (tautologically
self-evident but unhelpful); but if I understand what this passage is
referring to, that state of being-in-itself (pure existence) can only be
experienced to the extent that we are unable to slot things into the
conceptual grids that our hierarchical processing structures overlay
(automatically, in ordinary consciousness) on raw perception.

What did Wallace Stevens say - No idea without the thing itself?
Unfortunately, if we have the idea, it tends to take over the thing itself.
If the idea (name, concept, use etc.) is no longer available, the thing
remains mysterious, potentially at least anything. Is an avocado still an
avocado if all you can say about it is that it is a fascinating oval-shaped
green object/event in a shifting sea of perception (not that I could say
that at the time either, out loud or to myself, but that was more or less
what I was able to think about it without using words). Was it at that
moment an avocado? Well no, not for me in any case. It had become a
thing-in-itself, self-sufficient and existing but not identifiable, not in
the ordinary sense the subject of thoughts about it, not one example bound
to a class of things/relationships...and certainly not an eternal Idea or
Ideal unless by that one means something other than the
blueprint-of-the-physical-manifestation concept, which is much more bound
up with language than the state I'm referring to here.

If one wishes to argue that such perceptions are the result only of a
temporarily deranged subjectivity and have no general significance, I would
simply offer what others have said many times before, that everything we
know is known subjectively in this way, and that, useful as it is, a
scientific consensus type of reality is only one of the inter-subjective
descriptions available to us.

The paradoxical thing about all this is that in order to experience/know
the unity underlying phenomena it seems one has to eradicate all "higher"
concepts and relationships and thus render oneself truly useless. I suspect
if God exists he doesn't know the meaning of avocados either, much less the
meaning of ground-of-being (but then do we know the meaning of these words
either? Only relatively speaking, by a process of eliminating what they
absolutely can't mean...)

If I may quote the whimsical and wistful Nick Drake on this and related
real-life dilemmas and confusions of meaning, relationship, consciousness,
identity, being and becoming, and other Big Concepts:

I could have been a sailor, could have been a cook
A real live lover, could have been a book
I could have been a signpost, could have been a clock
As simple as a kettle steady as a rock
I could be
Here and now
I would be I should be
But how?
I could have been
One of these things first
I could have been
One of these things first

I could have been your pillar, could have been your door
I could have stayed beside you, could have stayed for more
I could have been your statue
Could have been your friend
A whole long lifetime could have been the end
I could be yours so true
I would be, I should be through and through
I could have been
One of these things first
I could have been
One of these things first.

I could have been a whistle, could have been a flute
A real live giver, could have been a boot
I could have been a signpost, could have been a clock
As simple as a kettle, steady as a rock
I could be even here
I would be, I should be so near
I could have been
One of these things first
I could have been
One of these things first.


Is anyone interested in talking about the relatively fixity or fluidity of
T's symbolism? Symbols can confound conceptual grids too, even if the only
way we can talk about that is (sigh) in conceptual grids (or in some kind
of meta-poetry).

