>Just saw Sakarov's Mother-Son and was very disappointed. He's obviously
>influenced by Tarkovsky, but with Sakarov it's all superficial. The images
>were --dare I say--cliche (e.g. dark clouds for brooding).  All style,
>little substance.  Few words (like Tark) but the words weren't meaningful.
>I hope Angelopolous, who I've read is somewhat like Tarkovsky, doesn't turn
>out to be such a disappointement.

I liked Mother and Son a great deal and disagree with every judgment made
here. So I'd be interested in hearing others' reactions to it. I wonder if
it should be measured against T though; certainly Sokurov has talked about
the differences in intent and approach, although like T's work it turns on
questions of faith and faithfulness. But Mother and Son is a two-character
work and narratively and conceptually it is very pared-down compared to
pretty much anything of T's; that doesn't make it superficial or cliched
however. Its images are exceptionally beautiful, as is its soundtrack. It's
almost a silent film in many ways, and is experienced more like visual art
and poetry than like most narrative cinema. Simply as an evocation of the
dying process it is unlike anything else I've seen.

As for Angelopoulos, prepare to be disappointed unless you go back to his
less sententious pre-90s work.

How about Gianni Amelio's Lamerica? I think there's a certain Tarkovskian
aura to its images and some of its incidents, even perhaps its narrative
trajectory, though some of its premises are very different.

