Scott, you write:


>I am certainly capable of being repressed -- as some have suggested here
>on the list. I never thought that my friend Carl was gay throughout the
>years that we spent together. He told me after we graduated, and I was
>surprised. I realize now that I was keeping this knowledge from myself, to
>protect myself, to protect our friendship. In a way it was a kind of tacit
>agreement -- although he was conscious of the arrangement and I was not.
>
>This was a very subtle form of homophobia. It was not antagonistic, as you
>can see. Still it was an unconscious fear that led me to a slightly
>distorted view of reality. I bet I still have a slightly distorted view of
>reality. I'm a great deal more self aware now than I was twenty years ago,
>but I still find that my mind takes care of things with out telling me all
>the details. I think this is normal.

I really appreciated this story, Scott. But consider also (as no doubt you
have) that internalized homophobia is something that gay people have to
struggle with daily. If your best friend couldn't tell you he was gay when
(presumably) it mattered, that was as much his problem as yours. Did he
ever discuss what it meant to him not to feel he could be exactly who he
was with you? What he was probably protecting was your sensitivity about
the subject (or his projection of that). And that may have had a profound
cost for him - or it may not have, depending on how he felt towards you.
And if he loved you he would also have been protecting himself from having
to deal with the anticipated rejection of those feelings (as he presumably
knew you were straight). And it may be that subconsciously you didn't trust
him enough on that score to make the subject even available to you to
possibly bring up with him (anyway the onus was always on him as the
different one, wasn't it?) And so, as you say, people protect each other in
a conspiracy of silence to save what they feel they have together from
possible conflict. It can be a deadly form of kindness. Under the
circumstances it *was* probably a kindness, but the circumstances are
anti-life. Privacy is a good thing insofar as it maximizes one's freedom
from others, but to the same degree it's very bad at maximizing one's
freedom with others.

To get back to Tarkovsky and Russia, it seems from what our Russian members
have said that men can be physical and even up to a point sensual with each
other as long as no homoeroticism is involved, but then the lavender
curtain comes crashing down so to speak - as it does say in any North
American locker room if someone glances the wrong way. But surely we should
throw out all these categories that help shore up the bad old concept of
masculinity, the one that can't stand without rejecting its feminine
shadow.

Obviously there's a continuum involving various degrees of bisexuality, not
necessarily acknowledged as such (and in an ideal world not having to be
acknowledged or identified as anything!). If Tarkovsky was bisexual - and
academic writers like Petrie are usually very conscious of how they phrase
anything to do with personal or sexual questions; if what they assert was
based only on speculation they would have said so - why should we protect
him from the charge rather than exploring how it might have played out in
his work and his life, including if possible asking people who knew him
what they think? It strikes me as not in the spirit of his work to place
limits on what can or should be said (apart from the usual limits of libel
and decency). Tarkovsky was not one to toe the social line...

>
>And I did think you had an interesting point. But fascism is another very
>complex subject. Have you read Susan Sontag's essay "Fascinating Fascism"?
>In it she suggests that certain artistic expressions are indicative of
>fascism: Art Deco, the Symbolists, she even mentions a few films Fantasia,
>Kubrick's 2001. I see what she's talking about , though I don't agree with
>her conclusion.
>
>I've often wondered what she would say about Tarkovsky's aesthetics.

