<x-rich>Hey Seamus


Well I've written another long one... I'm terribly sorry ... hey did I
mention that I was glad your back?

<paraindent><param>right,left</param>

> I distinctly remember seeing one of the women from earlier in the
movie in the

>crowd at the end. I remember her only because she looks exactly like
the

>mother of an old friend. .... After all, unlike

>the city folk in Rome, the townspeople actually do run to help
Gorchakov.

</paraindent>

Is the woman mulling around in the mud the one you remember? Dark hair
... kind of resembles G's Russian wife....  As for the other, it's G's
driver who runs to G's aid, right? The people I'm refering to is
strictly the group gathered at the far end of the pool. 


But never mind all that now, I've just looked at it again and you are
right to balk at the idea of film set self-awareness thing. Funny how
memory serves-- I swear I can see a different shot in my mind, with
<italic>scores</italic> of people! Could someone have re-editied my LD
copy and replaced the shot with one of less people? 


I<italic> have</italic> dreamed I was watching unseen footage from T's
films before -- anyone else?


So even as they do easily pass for villagers and hotel patrons, I think
the substance of my point still holds ... I do feel there is a bit of a
jarring effect after watching G alone in that long take  and then
suddenly look up and see that people have been gathering and watching.
The intensity of the privacy is interupted ... and emphasised.

<paraindent><param>right,left</param> 

> a novel by social critic Theodore Roszak called

>Flicker that you might enjoy. Via a pretty good conspiracy plot it
constructs

>an alternate history of cinema that derives it's origins from the
Egyptian

>priesthood and Knights Templar. Sort of a Foucault's Pendulum of film
history.

>I wonder if Roszak hadn't read this passage--he must have.

</paraindent>

That sounds worth checking out, thanks for the referance, indeed. Its
bound to have some legitamacy in principle ... if we agree that Greek
theater began as Mystery rites. 



Well I might as well tell you those quotes were from Morrison, the
lizard kid -- they are from "The Lords". I bought it years ago and
shleved it. I picked it up a few months back for god knows why and read
a few pages and was mildly impressed. I read the whole thing and was
more impressed --then I read it again  (its less than 100 pages I
think) and noticed that he's actually weaving some pretty fundamental
and strong ideas together. That doesn't show from the little I posted.



One bit I liked was that he reversed the Oedepus act of withdrawing 
completely into the body by putting out his eyes when he says that the
body has become a "dry stalk to support these two soft insatiable
jewels":


<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param><smaller>There are no
longer "dancers," the possessed. The cleavage of men into actor and
spectators is the central fact of our time. We are obsessed with heroes
who live for us and whom we punish. If all the radios and televisions
were deprived of their sources of power, all books and paintings burned
tomorrow, all shows and cinemas closed, all the arts of vicarious
existence . . .


We are content with the "given" in sensation's quest. We have been
metamorphosised from a mad body dancing on hillsides to a pair of eyes
staring in the dark.


</smaller></paraindent><smaller>(Clearly we are great consumers .. but
do we consume most with our eyes?)

 

</smaller>Anyway This is the continuity he's building when proposes
such high faith in the priority of film, that it "runs on without any
eyes". I think it's a kind of poetic way to express our subordination,
being what I call<italic> fascist subjects</italic>.


<paraindent><param>right,left</param>><<<<Metamorphose. An object is
cut off from its name, habits, associations.

>Detached, it becomes only the thing, in and of itself. When this

>disintegration into pure existence is at last achieved, the object is

>free to become endlessly anything.>>

</paraindent>

I keep thinking he's talking about a<italic> metaphore</italic> here. 


Its funny that you and Tony both seem to have slightly different
subjective points of view here. If I understand correctly you are
<italic>observing</italic> the object, subjectively (hence its need to
be recognisable as something known to the observer) and Tony is
<italic>identifying </italic>with the object.


As I understand Morrison's messy mystical museings, I think he's
continuing his theme on the terrifying consequences of the spectator's
(voyeur's) potential for endless identifications. (I
<italic>think</italic>...)


<paraindent><param>right,left</param> The assumption here seems to be
that a thing is not in a

>state of pure existence if it is bound to labels, uses, etc. Pure
existence,

>it would seem to me, would be just such bindings and associations.
Being, by

>which I mean the state of being, is not the ability to become
"endlessly

>anything"--but the state of being SOMETHING, even several things.
Being

>anything is, ultimately, the same as being nothing--i.e. not existing
at all.


</paraindent>

I think you an Jim Mo agree about the potentiality of the object in
becoming a subject. Reminds me of Domenico's "Where am I when I am not
in my head?"

<paraindent><param>right,left</param>

> Influence is always a tricky issue--some

>allusions are blatant, others subtle, others inadvertent. I think
your

>connection of Mann's Death in Venice to Nostalghia some time ago (that
was

>you, wasn't it Scott?) is a good example of either subtle or
inadvertent

>influence. The presence of religious painting and orthodox ideas (such
as

>Thomas is one to point out) are usually blatant or subtle. The Milton

>connection seems to me at the very least unconscious, if not simply
the result

>of similar thinking (with, albeit a common basis.)

</paraindent>

To speak plainly, I think the characteristic of funneling into privacy
was not an act of borrowing, as you seem to be agreeing, it was due to
some common fundamental issues both men were dealing with. But who
knows, I'm sure Tark had<italic> heard </italic>of Mr. Milton....


In some ideal way I guess we would like all transmissions of culture
from one generation to the next to be unconchuss.( a cheap word, no?) 
But it doesn't matter much to me, I guess. We all surly agree that
culture gets passed on through our mental activities ... (we haven't
figured out how to grow math-skill pills on bushes yet.) It's easy to
see how some things are handed down, others ...not easy to see. They
seem to move, as you say, indirectly. Some ideas appear and dissapear
at the periphery of others, attached to them like they are...
symbiolic.


I think these is called <italic>Synchronic</italic> events.. opposed to
the <italic>diachronic</italic>... if I understand them. 


Anyway, isn't this kind of transmission of culture far more
interesting? More so than the cases where one guy READS another and
thinks "Oh yeah that's a good idea, I think I'll decide to write a book
kinda like that only different, cause I think that's a good idea that I
ought to rite about." 


Having said that ... I DO think that Death In V was on T's mind with
Nastolghia! Admitedly because at this point in my hermenutic it serves
me to think so. (You know how you need all the help you can get when
things are still forming?) But most of all because its does service to
the imagination to think so... which is a very important litmus test to
me. I'm not thinking of the type of dirivation that is anything like an
adaptation. It's inspiration, a dialogue that <italic>provokes
</italic>thought when the reference is made, and more so does not
<italic>end</italic>  even then. 


I may change my mind later when I get where I want to go with it but
for now I'm sticking to it.


The details are fine and evasive and often of course, just subjective
and personal. I'm not ready to show my hand , here. Such things take
time to properly rationalize! I thought I could get some thoughts
worked out during the discussion w/ Tony but I got doused while
splashing around in the <bold>shallow </bold>water of whether or not T
was bisexual. Guess I should just head on down to the deep end. For the
record, thats another thing... an impossible distinction (Bi/not Bi?). 
Who knows? I don't think he was an astronaut, either. These might be
methods for simply getting to another space. 


But then again maybe he faked his death and he's up there in the
spacestation MIR with Jim Morrison having cocktails singing "We all
live in a Yellow Submarine".


S




 


