...and now Morrison (who was of course a film student at UCLA before
getting into music).

>Anyway This is the continuity he's building when proposes such high faith
>in the priority of film, that it "runs on without any eyes". I think it's
>a kind of poetic way to express our subordination, being what I call
>fascist subjects.

That's plausible. But he also seems to be saying something else. I haven't
read The Lords, but he seems to be suggesting that as a 20th century rite
cinema has some existence and even function when it's not being paid
attention to and thus not making us into voyeurs. Perhaps somehow a
parallel with those performances for the gods that take place on certain
busy yet ritually significant Bangkok street corners, and that no human
(apart from the performers) need even notice, but that are necessary to
keep things in balance. On the other hand this doesn't really make any
sense: cinema is already absence/history, detached from the body - a
one-way, basically non-participatory medium for spirit voyages, and fixed,
a foregone conclusion without the possibility of deviation or present acts
of subversion; for it also not to be seen is to render it a mere piece of
machinery, one soon on the way to the junkheap. And if Morrison is talking
from the point of view of the filmmaker rather than the audience, how would
he reconcile these comments with The Doors' performances? Taking the
audience-beast with him to some place way beyond safety and decorum was the
whole point, wasn't it? Cinema just can't do that nearly as directly; what
kind of cinema really "returns us to anima, religion of matter"? (Maybe I'm
being too literal here. Maybe part of his point is that cinema impacts
powerfully on the body but is also light, immaterial, and therefore can
bring together many materialities and metaphors in a short time, unlike the
theatre, which is bounded by a particalar space.)

[Help, I'm confused!]

>><<Metamorphose. An object is cut off from its name, habits, associations.
>>Detached, it becomes only the thing, in and of itself. When this
>>disintegration into pure existence is at last achieved, the object is
>>free to become endlessly anything.>>
>
>I keep thinking he's talking about a metaphore here.

But metaphors, slippery as they are, still cannot be endlessly anything.
Pure existence is meaningless, metaphors are meaningful only to the extent
that they create some intersecting semantic nets that we hadn't considered
before. Metaphors are never things in and of themselves, they're always
several or many things at once, beyond singularity. (Would Barthes
disagree?) Again, maybe I'm totally missing the point.

>
>Its funny that you and Tony both seem to have slightly different
>subjective points of view here. If I understand correctly you are
>observing the object, subjectively (hence its need to be recognisable as
>something known to the observer) and Tony is identifying with the object.
>
>As I understand Morrison's messy mystical museings, I think he's
>continuing his theme on the terrifying consequences of the spectator's
>(voyeur's) potential for endless identifications. (I think...)

I thought he was celebrating it. If we identify with something we are no
longer detached, there is the possibility of becoming what we experience
rather than merely thinking about it:

>Strange, fertile correspondences the alchemists sensed in unlikely orders
>of being. Between men and planets, plants and gestures, words and weather.
>These disturbing connections: an infant's cry and the stroke of silk; the
>whorl of an ear and an appearance of dogs in the yard; a woman's head
>lowered in sleep and the morning dance of cannibals; these are
>conjunctions which transcend the sterile signal of any "willed" montage.
>These juxtapositions of objects, sounds, actions, colors, weapons, wounds,
>and odors shine in an unheard-of way, impossible ways.

Yeah, metamorphosis. You still have to see the images though for it to
happen. But certainly a radical cinema of transformation is what he's
talking about. I just don't think he's being very consistent in how he
talks about it.

I think what he's envisioning breaks down narrative far more than Tarkovsky
ever did. Morrison seems to be suggesting a poetic politics of cinema (this
was around '68 after all) but one equally far removed from the
intellectualism of a Godard and the socially uncommitted formalism of much
of the New American Cinema (though maybe there's a connection with Anger,
Jacobs, Pat O'Neill...). Yet one feels he would at least have admired
Tarkovsky for his "shining juxtapositions".

Tony





Tony Reif (Songlines Recordings)


