<x-rich>Hey Tony


Wish I had more time to clarify these fascinating issues. I'm leaving
town for a few days and I'm trying to get some thoughts down before I
forget the thread. I hope I havn't botched the subject up too badly.


Your letter was very good. Forcing me to think more decidedly from a
perspective uncommon to my daily one. I appreciate that greatly.

<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

>a conspiracy of silence ..... It can be a deadly form of kindness.
Under the

>circumstances it *was* probably a kindness, but the circumstances are

>anti-life.

</paraindent>

The generalazations have caught up with me... I know I'm probably more
guilty than most though. Anyway, you'll have to take my word on this I
can't imagine that Carl and I could have been closer friends no matter
how much sex we could have had. Sometimes the limits and tensions serve
us in their own ways don't you think?  Life being a big wad of psychic
surprises. Life without suffering is the most reprehensible form of
death. In my absurd opinion. Of course ideally we should be allowed to
chose our suffering, but I'm not mature enough for that.


<italic>Nastolghia</italic>, for me, is the ultimate failure of<italic>
all</italic> our relationships, even through the best of our multi
faceted modes of identification. From cultural heritage down to an
identification with the sex drive. Gorchakov seems to have found an
alienation that reminds me of Maimonodes' negative theology: He know
longer knows who he is, but he knows who he is not. Gorchakov seems to
be to be unsatisfied with them all --- even as he feels the agonizing
loss of the kind of soul they provided.


I say this because I don't think we will ever create a social arena
that's for everybody... though we personally can  never give up
trying.

<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

 Privacy is a good thing insofar as it maximizes one's freedom

>from others, but to the same degree it's very bad at maximizing one's

>freedom with others.

</paraindent>


This is a well put thought, private identity is something I feel is
really deep trouble in media filled countries like this one. As a
matter of fact I can't say what it is. I have the feeling you are
talking about secrets, though. If so I'm with you 100%

<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

> But surely we should

>throw out all these categories that help shore up the bad old concept
of

>masculinity, the one that can't stand without rejecting its feminine

>shadow.


</paraindent>Another well put thought, as you go on to say there's a
continuum to our identity that is difficult enough to access as it is. 
But, careful with that Junging schtick, you might hurt somebody. Not
because I disagree but because its so much easier said than done! I'm
not one to encourage such naive notions as "getting in touch with your
shadow side" maybe I'm the psycho but some of my shadows are folks I
don't want anywhere near my kids or anyone elses. I toss em a bone and
a beer every now and then to keep them from starving to death and
taking me with them but otherwise I'm scared pretty much stupid by most
of them. The female one's you seem to be referring to don't bother me
as much, though. Except one <italic>Lilith the Lesbian</italic> she
gives me LOTS of trouble. I did appear in a film in drag once. (don't
go trying to rent it... sorry) 

<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

>>In it she suggests that certain artistic expressions are indicative
of

>>fascism: Art Deco, the Symbolists, she even mentions a few films
Fantasia,

>>Kubrick's 2001. I see what she's talking about , though I don't agree
with

>>her conclusion.

>>

>>I've often wondered what she would say about Tarkovsky's aesthetics.

>

>Well, what would she have said? What would you say?


</paraindent>Well I'm not quite fresh on the subject right now so I'll
just whiz through some of my impressions.


I think Fascism is a specific historical circumstance. I don't agree
that it's a phenomenon with symptoms. Hitler was an artist. I'll give
him that. He may be the greatest artist of the twentieth century even.
(Artist: NOT synonymous with "good")


There are aesthetics of power, beauties that energize us. But the
closer we get to the nerve the more we need insulation, and some kind
of method of retreval.  


Those areas of mystical sources don't always come with instructions.
Nothing wrong with power per se.. there's good and bad. But even those
distinctions are illegible. The powers we invite or ingest keep us
vital and viable. They can also be deadly destructive and so we need
equally powerful containers. Which are composed of equally destructive
energies. ("When I hear the word culture I pull my gun")  


So yes those aesthetics can be dangerous, though I wouldn't say
Goebbles or Riefenstahl are any more central representatives than
Christianity or MTV. Calling all formal compositions with mystic
dimensions "Fascist tendencies" is no help at all. I think they can
also be called "Romantic".


Thanks for the reference to Gianni Amelio. I'm completely ignorant
until I read this.

http://www.stanford.edu/~cjacoby/amelio.html



S



