  Based on the surviving footage, some people believe that "Que viva México"
had the potential of being Eisenstein's greatest film.  ...we will never know.

Some additional backstory [all info culled from David A. Cook's "A History of
Narrative Film" (New York, 1981)]:

1) 1930 Eisenstein signs a contract with the Mexican Film Trust, a corporation
made up of the American novelist Upton Sinclair and other investors, to make a
film in Mexico.
2) Eisenstein later writes that the film was to have been "four novels framed
by prologue and epilogue, unified in conception and spirit, creating its
entity."
3)1932 Sinclair orders that further filming be abandoned, and correctly
accuses Eisenstein of far exceeding his budget.
4) Sinclair reneges on his promise of sending the negative to Moscow for
Eisenstein to edit and finish, and instead sells the footage to the
independent producer Sol Lesser.
5) Lesser cuts part of one episode into a silent melodrama of revenge titled
"Thunder Over Mexico" (1933), and parts of the epilogue into another titled
"Death Day" (1934).  Both films are critical and commercial failures.
6) Remaining footage find their way into various documentaries on the making
of "Que viva México!", and ultimately into the archives of the Museum of
Modern Art in New York.

Further Reading: Ronald Gottesman, "The Making and Unmaking of 'Que Viva
México!'" (Bloomington, Ind., 1971)

Reichart,
Los Angeles, U.S.A.

