>Hi!
 Yes. I agree with you on this. I know that i am in the minority, but
I personally feel that Nostaghia was it: His penultimate work
(remember, after all how it ends). 
Logically, there was no where for him to go after that. Excpet of
course to purgatory.

Aestheticly, the Sacrifice holds no surprises; little of the intuitive
geniuse of his better works. His manipulation of space and time is
reduced to pat formulars (45 min 'chunks', or cycles. = to the
biorythmic patterns of perceptual activity). because of this there is
a particular kind of ridgedness present. The 'padding out' that T.
utilizes habitually in his works is strained. The reduncies faulters
on occation and slips into catatonia. The self-reflexivity reduced to
a shallow expedienfcy. It fails to reach the sublime (taking the
moment beyond the artifice) hight of the baths sequences that
finalises Nostalgia.

With all of his precarious circumstances, T. was a desperate filmaker.
Perhaps he wrote himself out to early. The fact remains though, in the
end, that he was a walking deadman, and he knew it to. 
If there is anything to salviged from the  Sacrifice it can only be
gained from understanding the film this way. Tarkovsky faced the
ultimate nightmare of the artist: the irrovokable knowelled that his
best work was behind him, and this is a terrible fate for somebody who
entreanched thier life so much in their art. 

I suspect that there is a cautionary tale somewhare in their for all
of us...

