In a message dated 98-08-31 04:33:02 EDT, you write:

<< my initial impression was that tarkovsky was trying to do a lot, perhaps
 too much, in his last work, and failed to achieve anything. and i
 generally don't think that a complex symbolic design alone would make a
 great work of art. >>

Hey Henry,

First of all, I apologize for being snotty.  Your criticisms of "The
Sacrifice" are quite legitimate.  Actually, I found it pretty stupefying
myself, the first time.  I was crying by the end but I didn't know why.  When
I advised you to just keep watching once a year I really meant more than
anything that I can explain what a symbol might mean, but that this won't
carry any emotional weight for you until something has happened in your life
which will bring the message home.  I only really felt as though I'd begun to
understand this film after nursing a close friend through the last several
months of his struggle with cancer.  Watching him lose everything, even his
physical body, to disease and still keep his smile, still keep his faith, was
an indescribable experience for me.  Afterward, I saw "The Sacrifice" again
and cried again.  I still can't really articulate why but I believe that I
understand it, even if I can't communicate it to you.

But hey, that's just my opinion.

