Welcome to the discussion group--the shouting is atypical. And be sure to read
over what Aphrodite has to say more carefully, don't let the tone fool you.
She has a lot to say.

Seeing Tarkovsky on the big screen is essential. I won't go so far as many
might and say that you haven't seen his work until you've seen it on the big
screen--that's bullshit--but it definitely adds layers. Most noticeably: the
change is film stocks becomes far more noticeable, and the textures far more
varied. This is especially true of his last four films where the use of
sepiatone and other monochromatic film stocks is so prevalent. Stalker, for
instance, has a rusty hue on the big screen which gradually settles into sepia
and then into a washed out color. Much of that subtlety is lost on video.
Also: the long-takes show their success in larger venues when your eyes can
roam about and look at the complexity of the filmed world just like they would
in the real world--no shitty cuts and close-ups to tell you what to look at.
Plus there's just the usual advantages of seeing things as they were designed
to be seen, etc.

Seamus

