Andrew wrote: 
 
 <<Yes. I agree with you on this. I know that i am in the minority, but
 I personally feel that Nostaghia was it: His penultimate work
 (remember, after all how it ends). 
 Logically, there was no where for him to go after that. Excpet of
 course to purgatory.>>
 
 First off--you are absolutely correct in calling Nostalghia Tark's
 "penultimate work"--it was. Especially since penultimate means, simply, "next
 to last." Still, I also tend to see it as his greatest film. Nonetheless, I
 disagree with your statement that he had nowhere left to go from Nost.--his
 next film, in this sense, is the logical conclusion of Nostalghia.
 
 Nostalghia, as I have argued at length in the past, is a concerned with women
 and motherhood. The film begins with a visiting to the painting of the Virgin
 Mother, a Catholic litany on the attributes Mary (mother of this mother of
 that . . .), a sexton's lecture on the place of women in society, a narrator
 who longs for his wife and children, a dream sequence that shows his pregnant
 wife on a bed outlined dimly against the infinite darkness of space (she
seems
 to be floating--the eternal mother), countless images of babies (including
 that darkly hideous painting in Domenico's home).   It is no surprise then to
 find that the film is dedicated to the memory of Tarkovsky's mother--I will
 not take the time to interpret the film, simply to point out a thematic
 preoccupation.
 
 The Sacrifice: this film is similar to Nostalghia and is, I would argue, a
 continuance of the ideas in Nostalghia--except that here it is the Father/son
 relationships that dominates. Little Man and Alexander, the metaphor of the
 tree, the sacrifice of the father for the son--the film is dedicated by Tark
 to his own son. The films are inextricably interwoven--rhapsodies on an
 infinite theme. Look at other similarities: both films feature purging by
fire
 (sacrifice), both contain holy fools, both contain miniatures (in Sacrifice
of
 the house--as made by little man, in Nost of the valley in Domenico's home). 
 
 Does this repetition indicate that Tarkovsky was all out of things to say? I
 think not. In the Sacrifice we see a stunning meditation on the difficulty of
 passing on the wisdom one has attained in one's life--the impossibility of
 completely transferring what one has learned to the next generation. Little
 Man has retained the ritual his father introduced to him of watering the
 tree--but the films ends with his echoing one of the first things his father
 says at the beginning of the film, in the form of a question: " 'In the
 beginning was the word' why is that Papa?" But Alexander has renounced
 speech--as we all must some day.
 
 To me The Sacrifice is a fitting close to a splendid career. True, I think
 Nostalghia was the pinnacle of that career--but The Sacrifice is among his
 strongest films--technically and ideologically.
 
 Seamus
 
 
  

