Seamus says,

> Does this repetition indicate that Tarkovsky was all out of things to say? I
> think not. In the Sacrifice we see a stunning meditation on the difficulty of
> passing on the wisdom one has attained in one's life--the impossibility of
> completely transferring what one has learned to the next generation. Little
> Man has retained the ritual his father introduced to him of watering the
> tree--but the films ends with his echoing one of the first things his father
> says at the beginning of the film, in the form of a question: " 'In the
> beginning was the word' why is that Papa?" But Alexander has renounced
> speech--as we all must some day.

But consider that Little Man is about 7...whereas T's own sons were about
23 (Arseny) and 14 (Andrei) when The Sacrifice was made (although younger
when the script took shape in the early 80s). So if this was T's thematic
intention it seems he stacked the cards against success by having the kid
be so young, though according to Andrei the relationship *is* modelled on
theirs.

As Sarvenaz suggests, the end of the film is nevertheless very very moving.
Little Man speaks, somehow a small "miracle" has occured (even though it
perhaps was likely to happen/did happen anyway naturally, as we don't know
that Little Man was unable to speak before his operation, his mute
condition may have been temporary), and what he says brings the film and
life full circle. What is affirming is that he got the main point, and that
he asks the question even if there is no one to answer. (And there never
really is anyone or Anyone to answer even in T's world, we all have to make
up our own answers, as Alexander himself does I think through his
sacrifice. Although this may seem a very agnostic and subjective position
given some of T's own statements about The Sacrifice, I feel the film
supports it through the obvious negative as well as positive effects of
Alexander's actions, the ambiguous dreamscape in which the sacrifice is
conceived and undertaken (or merely imagined), and the impossibility of
confirmation that it was answered. As in Roublev, Solaris, Stalker and
Nostalghia, we are faced with a mystery, and the characters' faith(fulness)
is as much a humanistic, intensely personal response as a religious one.
One difference, in the later films faith is depicted as more deranged: it
seems the more T felt the need to make a positive statement, the harder it
was for him to show it simply and uncomplicatedly. Despite himself he never
became an ideologue.

To get back to Little Man and the question of transmission, in a way what
more can one ask for? Intellectual knowledge as well as personal
reflections, beliefs  and attitudes can be transmitted with some accuracy
and success down the generations through the written word, but as a
dramatic filmmaker and as a person T is engaged by the word made flesh, the
living example (unlike his supposed hero Bresson, who in my opinion dealt
more and more with abstractions; he even forced his actors not to be human,
which T could never do). Little Man's question is in fact the Word (latent
form or pattern, what underlies all thought and action, what endures,
however one sees it) being made flesh one more time, the very first
utterance (again) after a long period of gestation, the dead tree and the
boy growing "back" into life. Its purity and simplicity, like Little Man's
quiet, reflective demeanor and the highly formal ecstasy of Bach's music,
is so poignant by contrast with the crazed confusions and terrible
conflicts involved in Alexander's vow to save the world for his son.

For some reason it has always seemed to me that the cut from the fire scene
to this one hides a gap in time, that this scene could be days or months
later, marking a kind of return, a coming back together from that former
time: Maria by chance passing on her bicycle, the ambulance now returning
Alexander to his family...I know this doesn't really make sense and must
represent some kind of wish fulfillment on my part, but then the supposed
time continuity from the previous shot doesn't seem to make filmic sense
either (in particular isn't the ambulance going in the other direction, at
least in terms of screen direction if not "real" direction?). Since T has
compressed time emblematically into the fire scene's self-contained
plan-sequence (there was no one to call the ambulance after all...), the
final shots feel like an epilogue.

Tony


