Your response to my defense of The Sacrifice reads like an elaboration of my
argument, not a refutation of it. The end of the film is certainly an epilogue
and was probably intended as such.

I don't see where the age of Little Man in any way undermines the thematic
occupation of the film--I didn't say that the film was autobiographical,
simply that it was dedicated to his son. How does one pass on knowledge? An
older son would have complicated the relationship he was trying to portray--an
older son would have meant another type of movie (and maybe a very good
one)--something like the father/ son relationship in Mirror.

If The Sacrifice has a flaw it is the flaw that is inherent in all parables--a
reduction of complexity into simplistic categories. But that is also its
strength: simplicity. You argue that Tarkovsky was unable, despite himself, to
make simple statements about faith--this is not something to complain about.
Faith isn't simple--consider the story of the garden that Alexander tells
Maria. Simplicity is spoiled by tampering and structuring. So it is with the
Sacrifice: the message is at once simple in form (a parable) and incredibly
complex.

Much has been made of the fact that no one could have called the
ambulance--and, if one likes, it can be conceded that Tark nodded off here.
Honestly, I've never really cared much. It's like complaining about the
talking wolf in the story of Little Red Riding Hood--if you get hung up on
that you miss the point of the parable. Given the choice between continuity
and beauty, I'll take beauty.

Seamus         

