hi Seamus,

I really want to comment 2 things you have said :

a)

>  Nostalghia, as I have argued at length in the past, is concerned with women
>  and motherhood. The film begins with a visiting to the painting of the Virgin
>  Mother, a Catholic litany on the attributes Mary (mother of this mother of
>  that . . .), a sexton's lecture on the place of women in society, a narrator
>  who longs for his wife and children, a dream sequence that shows his pregnant
>  wife on a bed outlined dimly against the infinite darkness of space (she
> seemsto be floating--the eternal mother), countless images of babies (including
>  that darkly hideous painting in Domenico's home).   It is no surprise then to
>  find that the film is dedicated to the memory of Tarkovsky's mother--

.....apart of these obvious facts, one has to consider the more or less enigmatic
figure of Domenico. Who is really Domenico? The easy answer would be a 'holy
fool'; if so,  how does he fits in the pattern of 'motherhood' you have suggested
here? Because I cannot really understand the connection between the two themes....

And one more thing : at the dream sequence, we also see the girlfriend-
interpreter exchanging secrets with the mother.... we never hear , perhaps the
protagonist too, what the two women are really saying! This is also a strong and
somehow difficult to understand scene.... The Mother is passing secrets about the
son to the Woman? Is this a female conspiracy, or an attempt from his mother's
side to protect him by letting her know his sui generis nature?

But in Nostaghia the woman is never a woman really because a. she has voluntarily
renounced her child baring rights (she is beautiful and typically desirable but it
is clear that she is such not to facilitate nature but to achieve her own
egotistical means, she lacks the inner devotion to nature/God/man) b. she remains
a 'virgin' to the protagonist/poet...  So the whole presentation of motherhood is
alien to real life; it is only an image in a church, a dream, a remembrance, a
nostalgic longing for the Woman ; In reality the woman is not an object of desire,
intercourse is denied, pregnancy avoided, and the 'meeting' of man and woman
produces only sterility and frustration.... a fertile ground for dreams, memory
and past to be revisited. I can think a few things here but it would be too easy
in this point for me to blame once again A.Tarkovsky for not being able to adapt
to the woman's rights movement...  Even if it is so, I don't think he is alone
there! And maybe by achieving one good cause , woman has lost track of the meaning
of 'sacrifice' - essential to motherhood in a way... Negative, difficult feelings
thrive in his last 2 films... A reversed world order, perhaps.

b) you say.....

>  In the Sacrifice we see a stunning meditation on the difficulty of
>  passing on the wisdom one has attained in one's life--the impossibility of
>  completely transferring what one has learned to the next generation. Little
>  Man has retained the ritual his father introduced to him of watering the
>  tree--but the films ends with his echoing one of the first things his father
>  says at the beginning of the film, in the form of a question: " 'In the
>  beginning was the word' why is that Papa?" But Alexander has renounced
>  speech--as we all must some day.

Perhaps Alexander has renounced speech.... because he represents God, the Father,
in his celestial version but also the God inside every human being. We have heard
so many times of the 'Silent God' of our times who stays speechless in front of
the situation his creature created; the silent , meditative God that is no longer
the Action God for reasons perhaps beyond His own volition. So the child here
perhaps embodies the New type of God, the one that is to emerge out of the dead
ends his father's dominion has created. No one is to blame, and everybody has paid
his own debts; but the old must go and the new is  so young that it still needs
nurturing and time to develop. The outcome is yet uncertain.....  But how one can
describe all these feelings/thoughts without falling into the most dreaded
situation of offending God? Perhaps the only way to talk about God, to start a
dialogue with Him is to be cryptical, not in an attempt to confuse your fellow
humans but to show the appropriate respect to Him... The Son still immature but
innocent, with a spontaneous wisdom, re-examines the basics his father handed down
to him; the function of the mind, and his material manifestation: speech,
language. He still waters the dead tree in a scene that evokes japanese landscapes
and rituals. But we all see it through the eyes of the departing God; the lonely,
archetypal, leader who's grown desperate and dysfunctional, uncomfortable with his
own achievements... self-destructive even...

it's funny really : like an old rock star...

a.

