<x-rich>Friends and lovers:


Something that troubles me is: what is involved with the covert malice
that Alexander has toward his son? 


Alexander's slow growing self awareness seems to be a slow progression
in his life. ("A man who is developing a conscience" is  T's
description of the off screen father in <italic>Mirror)</italic> 
Alexander quits the theater because of his sudden (perhaps belated)
discovery of the dishonesty of "acting". His imperceptive speculation
about why he quit theater led him to conceed that it was "possibly" due
to some kind of spite toward Adelaid (She loved him because he was an
actor so he quit). 


I cannot escape that the connection between "acting" in the sense of
entertainment is related to the problem of action in Nostalghia -- as
Seamus says there is a continuity between the two films. "words ,
words, words ...If only I could DO something."  Hamlet's preoccupation
with acting is appropriate here but wherein Hamlet was involved with
the family romance of Orestes -- the murder of the father, the son's
revenge on the mother --  (granted, Alexander feels dominated by
"Mother" Adilade's world) here the family romance is compounded with an
Oedipal touch as well. When father and son sit alone among the trees,
Alexander's hamletesqe silioquy progresses until he loses touch with
his son altogether. When he realises he has slipped into some peculiar,
distant, not- very -fatherly character, his son returns and suprises
him as a threat, attacking him from behind and there is bloodshed. Just
talking about action brings harm to Little Man. 


What sort of dark scenareo lies behind this situation where the boy's
ability to speak (certainly his only mode of power) has been sugically
removed by the elder men of the film? We can't deny that this has the
religious ring as a kind of imposed "vow" of silence. But what kind of
spirituality is this? 


No, none of these notions are logical but Alexander's mental state is
not relaible in the film. He appears to be growing paranoid about what
he has unconsously orchestrated... As the "Garden story"...Alexander
says: "My God what have I done?"


In the infernal regions of the unconscious children are routenly
sacrificed for the transmission of familial and cultural purposes and
love and murder mingle as the very air is filled with the invisable
forces of violent attractions and repulsions. This potential rage of
war and plunder is constantly  if only slightly being diverted by our
daily words and actions. Death stands at our side. What kind of world
is this that we are unloading on our children? One might try to move
away to an island or a distant mountain only to find the enemy is us.


No, Alexander does not quite appear to be this neurotic but hints of
these things seem to be circling him as the film develops. As the slow
descent into the night suggests we are heading toward a point of
reversal, where we suddenly  see these ominous imaginary forces
suddenly flip onto the forground. Via a consensus of fear.


I think Sacrifice is the film most commited to T's dipiction of dream
style. Where people talk and act not as the characters themselves but
as perverted characters. Everyone is filtered through the oneric
perception of ONE character. There are extended sequences in "Solaris"
and "Stalker" and shorter flourishes in the rest but Sacrifice is
devoted for the most part to the underside of the waking life.  the "45
min 'chunks', or cycles. = to the biorythmic patterns of perceptual
activity" are REM cycles, roughly. 


The reversal is completed at the end of the film as Alexander takes the
sacrifice upon himself, imposing the silence upon himself seems -in
this context an act of faith that his son will no need the forced hand
of the father and by extention our culturations. Not a small act of
faith having seen the horrible swarms of hidden motives that humans
have, the unearthly powers that collective action is intended to
cultivate. 


When Abraham embraced the horrific religion of the locals having heared
the command of GOd to sacrifice his only child, he too displayed a
momentary faith in the most offensive kind of pagan practice our
civilisation has seen.  But this <italic>Akkida </italic> was an ironic
"binding": it was the binding that liberates.  For as maddening as it
is there is a quality in our best efforts to rid the world of evil that
is itself destructive. Our religions, our science, our predispositions,
codes of certainties are all "endless approximations". As always T was
advancing a paradox that we needn't worry about losing our fearful grip
on understanding, because when we do what will we find will only be
more of our understanding. Supressing negativity does not make it so--
even if it does produce "revelations". These are still only foolish
consistancies.


Its hard to remember the first impression of a film that takes repeated
screenings to appreciate but its clear that when Alexander burns the
house we are lead to suspect that Little Man may have been inside. The
monstrosity of Alexanders madness is only relived when we get that cut
to Little Man as he carries the water to the tree.  How ever much time
has passed is not clear but our relife indicates for the first time an
end to the nightmare.


Though it isn't clear that T <italic>knew</italic>  he was dying of
cancer when he made the film (TWT 348-9) being the morbidly aware soul
that he was I think its safe to say he knew he was dying when he
<italic>first began  </italic>making films. But like a Buddist T was
always imposing an optimism on his dour perception of life, family,
God, spirituality, art, film and religion. Letting go was his raison
detre... Letting go of his father, his mother, wife, children and his
films.  Letting go of interpretations -- the final judgment of this
terrific world of sublime highs and lows. 


Was <italic>Fear  </italic>the God that drove Alexander? He's not
saying. He only shows us the best that he can imagine.


Kierkigaard  imagined Abraham pretending to be insane so that his son
would not blame god for the madness, ALexander also hopes to take the
madness of the world upon himself, and free his son from a damning
predisposition. The world is redeemed. 


But what can we say in the audience?  He has again bound his son in a
knot of his own invention. T does not untie this knot for us, with his
film. The film is ours, its loops are the <italic>akkida  </italic>of
our own imagination. T only belies his choice in the dedication ... "hi
mom"!


<paraindent><param>right,right,right,left,left,left</param>Poetry whose
hidden subject is the anxiety of influence is naturally of a Protestant
temper, for the Protestant God always seems to isolate His children in
the terrible double bind of two great injunctions; "Be like Me" and "Do
not presume to be too like Me."

</paraindent>

Aphrodite misreads Shavarnez but we appreciate that when it is
provocative (and not too hurtful, I remind myself) . Actualy we can
have it no other way, because if we are not wasting our time here we
might be taking a bit of the poetic personality from T for ourselves.
If it was too presumptious for T himself to think that we are his
poetic partners do we dare not concede that we too become like the
poets who create and rapsodise as H Bloom says " by misreading one
another, so as to clear imaginative space for themselves" (Anxiety of
Influence P5)


We take these poetic movies into ourselves; after gestation and birth
we are unable to scorn them for thier weaknesses for they are
<italic>our  </italic>children now and to condemn them is to condemn
ourselves. Of course we are human and find that we can compensate by
shunting our disappontements through our contempt toward other people's
undisciplined kids.  My Tarkovsky is authentic --yours is not.


The solopsism is troubling , inevitable and a  sign of sychophancy I
suppose but it isn't sychophancy if we participate with the artist.
Still this requires an inordinant amount of unseeming trust toward one
"artist"/leader/mentor. Lots of time and gestation.  A devotion that
might appear distateful in others. We might call it obsessive but as
Mr. Bloom points out this is the nature of how a poets offspring
suffers as things are passed on -- not just consumed -- one "peers in
the mirror of his fallen precursor and beholds neither the precursor
nor himself but a Gnostic double, the dark otherness or antithesis that
both he and the precursor longed to be, yet feared..."


Is it so unatural to hope that we should do something with what we have
taken from this filmaker? Perhaps he was a person we might have known,
not a star of our projected ambition.  We needen't aspire to be famous
or earth shattering --- simply creative in our own impenatrable private
worlds -- that is the better part of being a "follower" no?  My hope is
that the music we share does not turn our bodies into a public
marketplace.



Sorry for the long, sloppy and turgid rush...


S







</x-rich>
