Aphrodite:

You make some interesting points.

a: as per Nostalghia. I agree that there is much that my observations does not
speak to. Domenico is an enigmatic figure--a repressed side of Gorchakov, I
think (hence the dream sequence where G sees D in the mirror). Part of
Nostalghia is concerned with the abandonment of motherhood--Eugenia is not
maternal in the least. Note that the images of babies are usually unhealthy
(that painting in Domenico's place is creepy, as is the detritus ridden baby
that is among the debris in the drowned pool at the end). I think this is part
of Domenico's significance within the interpretation I have been developing:
remember that he attempts to confine his wife and children. This is the
opposite of G., who flees his own wife and children. Again, I'm still working
on these issue--but they're irrefutably there. (I was heartened to find that
you found my observations "obvious"--when I mentioned them months ago I had to
defend them against your dear old friend mario almost daily!)

b: I do not tend to see Alexander as being emblematic of God. His act of
sacrifice is truly Christlike, if anything. He sacrifices himself that life
might continue--the difficulty is that Little Man must now live by his
father's actions. If you want to pursue the Xian interpretation: Little Man is
the first Xian, struggling to live by the Chrstilike example of his father--it
is noteworthy that the line "In the beginning was the word . . ." is from the
Book of John. But this interpretation has many problems, and it is probably
best to concede that, though Alexander has Christlike attributes towards the
end, that he is not meant to BE Christ.

Hmmmm.

At any rate, I hope I have established my true thesis: that the Sacrifice is
anything but one of Tark's weakest films.

Seamus   

