Hey Scott,

Your post is so full of interesting ideas and possibilities it's
frustrating not to be able to elaborate and pin some of them down with you
(for lack of time, and the need to really do this kind of brainstorming in
the instant give and take of a real conversation if each of our "creative"
misunderstandings of each other are not to proliferate into a truly
profound solipsism!).

But anyway, a couple of points that I really didn't get and a comment or two.

>
>But what can we say in the audience?  He has again bound his son in a knot
>of his own invention. T does not untie this knot for us, with his film.
>The film is ours, its loops are the akkida  of our own imagination. T only
>belies his choice in the dedication ... "hi mom"!

The dedication is to his son Andrei...a statement of hope for him and his
future. How does this belie the thematic you've been sketching in here? And
what do you mean by "his choice"? Also what is akkida?

>The solopsism is troubling , inevitable and a  sign of sychophancy I
>suppose but it isn't sychophancy if we participate with the artist. Still
>this requires an inordinant amount of unseeming trust toward one
>"artist"/leader/mentor. Lots of time and gestation.  A devotion that might
>appear distateful in others. We might call it obsessive but as Mr. Bloom
>points out this is the nature of how a poets offspring suffers as things
>are passed on -- not just consumed -- one "peers in the mirror of his
>fallen precursor and beholds neither the precursor nor himself but a
>Gnostic double, the dark otherness or antithesis that both he and the
>precursor longed to be, yet feared..."

Mailing list discussions like this are a kind of creative flexing that
presumably we don't find elsewhere (or we probably wouldn't be here). I'm
not a poet but poetic associations, ambiguities and paradoxes have always
interested me. The same kinds of subjective (mis)readings show up on the
Nick Drake list, and no doubt I contribute my share. Yes it can be
obsessive but it's our passionate response to something, someone who has
read our minds as it were. I don't know if we ever become the  Gnostic
double that Bloom talks about but to uncover one's thoughts about what
continues to touch one deeply is liberating somehow. It can take time
though to write with enough accuracy to be understood, and I often feel
that most people don't take the time to elaborate to the point where what
they say can be responded to without compounding the confusion or merely
exchanging generalities. Though I guess all any of us can do is put
something out there and see...

>Is it so unatural to hope that we should do something with what we have
>taken from this filmaker? Perhaps he was a person we might have known, not
>a star of our projected ambition.  We needen't aspire to be famous or
>earth shattering --- simply creative in our own impenatrable private
>worlds -- that is the better part of being a "follower" no?  My hope is
>that the music we share does not turn our bodies into a public marketplace.

Obviously I agree with the general idea, but your last sentence confuses
me. Surely this is at best exactly a disembodied form of communion, and not
the better for that! Not one I find satisfying even for as supposedly
"spiritual" a subject as T. So please explain your paradox or metaphor for
the intellectual stragglers among us.

Tony

Tony Reif (Songlines Recordings)


