<x-rich>Hey Tony


Good to hear from you. Yes, I'm sorry I didn't have time to clear up
such confusion as I obviously could have. I like to be eliptical but
some things were simply left unedited.



<paraindent><param>right,right,right,left,left,left</param>>>But what
can we say in the audience?  He has again bound his son in a knot

>>of his own invention. T does not untie this knot for us, with his
film.

>>The film is ours, its loops are the akkida  of our own imagination. T
only

>>belies his choice in the dedication ... "hi mom"!

</paraindent><paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

>The dedication is to his son Andrei...a statement of hope for him and
his

>future. How does this belie the thematic you've been sketching in
here? And

>what do you mean by "his choice"? Also what is akkida?

</paraindent>

About the dedication, you're right--another blunder.

 

The point was that I think the film ends without t commiting himself to
an interpretation to the dream he has shown us. Is there a "God" at
all? Is the son set upon any better course - with our without a God or
father (culture, patriarchal or whatever). 


T is perceptive to the point of leaving us profoundly disturbed, a real
choice can only be ours. His dedication "with hope and confidence" is
his most honest way of including his personal interpretation/choice.
That choice being to <italic>believe</italic> (?) that all the horrors
that we might dream to be haunting our actions may or may not be
ultimate causes (secret motives, suppressed nature, unconscious freud
((joke?)) But even if they are at the root of our limited being are
they  at the root of life/existence?.  


It's possible that beyond our understanding something we could describe
as an ultimate "good" intention may be "out" there.  Science might say
we have a fifty fifty chance in the war between light and darkness.
Such things are only a matter of opinion - science cannot help us where
we need help most. At the bottom of it all.


Over simply, T shows us a glass with water in it. He comments that he
thinks it's half full.



Akedah in Hebrew means "binding".


The "Akedah" is the term used in Jewish studies to refer to Abrahams
trial with his son Isaac. You know the story about God commanding
Abraham to sacrifice his "son, his only son" the son he had been
promised for forty some odd years  ... 


Abraham nearly goes through with the murder of the child but is
deterred at the last moment by an angel.


(BTW Muslems say it was not<italic> Isaac  </italic>who was involved,
it was his first son<italic> Ishmael</italic>  born of Abraham's
concubine Hagar).


<paraindent><param>right,right,right,right,left,left,left,left</param>

>>Is it so unatural to hope that we should do something with what we
have

>>taken from this filmaker? Perhaps he was a person we might have
known, not

>>a star of our projected ambition.  We needen't aspire to be famous
or

>>earth shattering --- simply creative in our own impenatrable private

>>worlds -- that is the better part of being a "follower" no?  My hope
is

>>that the music we share does not turn our bodies into a public
marketplace.

</paraindent><paraindent><param>right,right,right,left,left,left</param>

>Obviously I agree with the general idea, but your last sentence
confuses

>me. Surely this is at best exactly a disembodied form of communion,
and not

>the better for that! Not one I find satisfying even for as supposedly

>"spiritual" a subject as T. So please explain your paradox or metaphor
for

>the intellectual stragglers among us.

</paraindent>

Your misunderstanding is quite worthy! My intention may prove less
interesting -- but I explain: It is a referance to the rock and roll
bit between Sarvenaz and Aphrodite. I did make a sort of leap there.


This is a big subject. My opinion is that the intimate relationship
that popular music achieves with our personal bodies is openly degraded
by its publicity and proffessionalism -- which seems to be an
inevatable consequence of capatalism. My problem is I simply can no
longer ignore this when pursuing my needs there.  The natural conduits
between the music and our dancing reactions have strings attached. The
profiteer has greater and greater influence into my body. Unredeemably.
I have lost "hope and confidence " in the interests of the music
"icons".


Though I find it harder and harder to dance around the deception I do
manage every now and then. There are notable exceptions in the mix and
I do break down and purchase a ditty - for the body's sake.  Even a
prostitue needs love in whatever way he might manage to puchase it for
himself.


S

</x-rich>
