Scott said,
>
>This is a big subject. My opinion is that the intimate relationship that
>popular music achieves with our personal bodies is openly degraded by its
>publicity and proffessionalism -- which seems to be an inevatable
>consequence of capatalism. My problem is I simply can no longer ignore
>this when pursuing my needs there.  The natural conduits between the music
>and our dancing reactions have strings attached. The profiteer has greater
>and greater influence into my body. Unredeemably. I have lost "hope and
>confidence " in the interests of the music "icons".
>
>Though I find it harder and harder to dance around the deception I do
>manage every now and then. There are notable exceptions in the mix and I
>do break down and purchase a ditty - for the body's sake.  Even a
>prostitue needs love in whatever way he might manage to puchase it for
>himself.

Unless you're a musician you're not the prostitute! Are you literally
referring to dance music or to the whole popular music business and how our
bodies (and minds too sometimes) are colonized by the entertainment
industry?

Since I run my own record label I'm interested in these questions. I don't
want to take up much list bandwith on something this off-topic. But there
are other ways for the body to be moved by music than by the big beat. I'm
rather partial to the fragmented pulse-shards of avant-jazz, which, taken
to its extreme, destroys the beat by filling it in with everything it isn't
- and therefore allows you to move with any aspect of rhythm you respond to
from moment to moment (the acid of jazz? but not acid-jazz, which is surely
misnamed...). Of course most people can't stand the stuff, but its
anti-hierarchical form, in-the-moment collectively improvised nature, and
lack of commercial exploitability make it the most democratic music I know.

Tony

Tony Reif (Songlines Recordings)


