<x-rich>Tony,

Thanks for not taking my anti music rag too personal. I think its a
condition of our culture and not due to anyone's deliberate abuse. My
whole family are musicians, undoubtedly making this a sensitive subject
for me.


<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>>Unless you're a
musician you're not the prostitute! 

</paraindent>

Yeah I can see that. I was not a very good  musician, I could never get
over the dirty feeling.

<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

</paraindent>It's hard to express. Putting  money aside for a moment.
To me it feels like the popular "musician" today is pursuing identity
through territory (amassing an audience) ... and
<italic>bodies</italic>  are that territory. The music is the medium of
exchange. The "audience" gets more than sensual gratification, we get
identity through service... belonging.


Music is no longer simple, its full of cultural information...
semiotics and such. Music is flashed around for status. The idea that
art is more valuable than money is an old verity, now become a cliche
due to its availability. We might call this "aesthetic inflation".


But the bottom line is how it feels. Not just that we realize one day
that our emotions have been exploited but that even the emotions
themselves were unfounded. As if we were cultivated for this, from
childhood. As you said..."colonized by the entertainment industry".


<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>>I'm rather partial to
the fragmented pulse-shards of avant-jazz, which, taken

>to its extreme, destroys the beat by filling it in with everything it
isn't

>- and therefore allows you to move with any aspect of rhythm you
respond to

>from moment to moment ... Of course most people can't stand the stuff,
but its

>anti-hierarchical form, in-the-moment collectively improvised nature,
and

>lack of commercial exploitability make it the most democratic music I
know.

</paraindent>

Very sophisticated stuff, I love it too... from Coleman to Zorn... but
the desperation. Like women who wear veils to protect themselves from
exploitation. But its treatment of the body is more severe than that,
isn't it? It's more like those medieval chastity belts of iron. It's
hard to have immediate personal pleasure when  we are so defensive.
Media is too good.


One of the composers that is on that CD "Homage to Andrie Tarkovsky"
seems to be appropriate here. Luigi Nono. I don't know exactly how he
works but I know he has a great interest in chance, if not
improvisation per se.


S

</x-rich>
