>>I'm rather partial to the fragmented pulse-shards of avant-jazz, which, taken
>>to its extreme, destroys the beat by filling it in with everything it isn't
>>- and therefore allows you to move with any aspect of rhythm you respond to
>>from moment to moment ... Of course most people can't stand the stuff,
>>but its
>>anti-hierarchical form, in-the-moment collectively improvised nature, and
>>lack of commercial exploitability make it the most democratic music I know.
>
>Very sophisticated stuff, I love it too... from Coleman to Zorn... but the
>desperation. Like women who wear veils to protect themselves from
>exploitation. But its treatment of the body is more severe than that,
>isn't it? It's more like those medieval chastity belts of iron. It's hard
>to have immediate personal pleasure when  we are so defensive. Media is
>too good.

Avant-jazz can be pretty sensual, and certainly very physical, along with
its sometimes more intellectual pleasures, don't you think? With what's
called energy music you can experience an almost oceanic engulfment by that
excess of stimlulation striking you in waves that keep chaotically
intersecting until you find yourself the still point at the center (static
and ecstatic)....With another, sparer group you might be focusing on the
whole space in which the unpredictable interweaving of sound events is
occuring until your mind and senses fuse in a hyperreceptive state. I only
get defensive if I'm really tired, because then the music often overwhelms
me so I have to push it away, keep it "out there". But when I'm up for it,
and it's really good (of course lots of it is little more than banging
around), I can't think of any other music that so opens me up to the moment
of creation, *every* moment  And to make such music, at its best, must be
feel creation itself flowing through you. What more could anyone ask?

I hope this doesn't sound like a commercial. But I do think that many
people who like Tarkovsky for the space his films open up (both physical
and psychic) would like at least the more reflective and thoughtfully
structured end of avant-jazz quite a lot. As a producer I've worked with a
number of NY based artists like Ellery Eskelin and Chris Speed whose music
has that inner intensity I associate with T.

 >One of the composers that is on that CD "Homage to Andrie Tarkovsky"
seems to be appropriate here. Luigi Nono. I don't know exactly how he works
but I know he has a great interest in chance, if not improvisation per se.

Once the cameras were rolling of course T wasn't an improvisor (for that
you need a much cheaper format than 35mm!). Haven't heard a lot of
contemporary classical music and can't comment on Nono. I find most
serial-inspired music for example just too abstract and intellectual, often
not sensually appealing in its textures/timbres and style of enunciation
(phrasing etc.), and not really engaging rhythmically. I know, I know, I'm
a philistine. But sometimes these contemporary classical guys seem like
constipated wankers compared to the great jazz player/composers. And I'd be
glad for anyone's recommendations here: "avant-garde music T might have
liked".

Tony

Tony Reif (Songlines Recordings)


