In a message dated 98-09-04 04:05:02 EDT, you write:

<< Just a question: why americans are so complexed by the European
 Culture ? Your attitude is a
  reaction of frustration. In Europe, to talk about structuralism it's
 really ridiculous. Nobody use this word (if you want to be on the top
 of the wave culture read Derrida and the Diplomatic World (Le monde
 diplo' est je crois édité dans toute l'Europe (Grek, Deutch, etc.) ) 
 You don't even have the sense of ridicule. But you're good advantaged:
 i don't speak your 
 LANGUAGE) >>


I don't recall saying I was perplexed by European culture. I have read Derrida
(as well as Foucault, Barthes, Kristeva, Zizek, Baudrillard, and so on). My
background is in literary theory and I am well aware of the obsolescence of
Structuralism--which is why I lashed out so vehemently against your desire to
talk about technical and structural aspects of Tark's movies. I assumed that
you were attacking the interpretations of The Sacrifice etc. that I and others
had offered--if you were, instead, attacking silly discussions of Tarkovsky's
homosexuality, etc. then I agree with you.

I have consistedly pointed to Tarkvosky's technical innovations in my postings
over the months while also having to defend hermeneutic approaches to his work
time and again. So perhaps I was hasty. If I misunderstood your post, then I
am sorry. It sounded to me like you wanted to move away from interpretative
discussions of Tarkovsky and towards the sort of technical discussions that
are virtually the sole characteristic of American film criticism: critics in
this country can talk about angles and shot length for years without even
hinting that maybe a film actually has something to say. Formalism (in the
form of New Criticism) is still the pervasive approach to cinema in this
country--we look at the structure, length, and all the externals without ever
delving into content and the place of the film within larger contexts.

I am sorry that there is a language barrier--I'm afraid that, despite having
studied each for a time, my French, German, and Spanish are all inifinitely
inferior to your English.

Seamus

