In a message dated 98-09-04 14:16:44 EDT, you write:

<< It sounded to me like you wanted to move away from interpretative
 discussions of Tarkovsky and towards the sort of technical discussions that
 are virtually the sole characteristic of American film criticism >>

Obviously content and meaning are the important things, but don't dismiss
entirely the value of a brief discussion of structure.  After all, Tarkovsky
didn't psychically beam his ideas into our heads, he used sepcific actors,
settings, and yes, even camerawork.  Seamus, don't worry about defending
yourself.  One cannot watch this list for very long and doubt the breadth of
your scholarship.

But back to Nostalghia.  I have to agree somewhat with Aphrodite, I don't
think it's really a film about (certainly not for) women.  In many of his
films I keep seeing Parsifal, if you'll forgive me for getting a bit Jungian.
I keep seeing the wounded Fisher King, waiting for a holy fool to ask a
healing question.  This is a very male theme.  I keep thinking that if I pay
close enough attention to these films (except Solaris which I consider a
special case, more on that later) I'll find a map, one which will show me a
way to ... I'm not quite sure what.

