<x-rich>Hey Tony


<paraindent><param>right,right,right,right,left,left,left,left</param>>Once
the cameras were rolling of course T wasn't an improvisor ....

</paraindent>

<paraindent><param>right,right,right,right,left,left,left,left</param>>I
only get defensive if I'm really tired, because then the music often
>overwhelms...

</paraindent>

Sorry for the mistake, I was referring to musicians in both cases. 


The defensiveness I was talking about was what I hear in the music,  in
the strategies of creating music that indeed does reach the body (yes I
agree) but only by a dis-orginisation/ re-orginization. (Artaud's
<italic>body without organs  </italic>perhaps?) The corruptions in the
direct relationships between mind, body, ear and instrument have become
so noisy that some musicians resort to extreme methods to return to
sensual pleasure. Don't get me wrong I like it. We don't have much
choice left do we?


Artists like these have a kind of mission that once was an assault on
bourgeois taste but I don't see the term avant garde as appropriate due
to the crumbling faith in community.  It suggests an uniformity in the
ranks that can't be presumed anymore. I sort of think of these
aesthetic assaults as "sorties" and more analogous to terrorists. But
terrorism is only so if it is a public threat, and musicians cannot
pose an aesthetic force without some kind of representation in numbers,
a movement.  Hence my sense of futility. 


In the closing scene of<italic> Nostalghia </italic> the relationship
between the images, music and our bodies is disrupted. The <italic>Ode
to Joy </italic> is "cut up" in the diegesis  - from within the scene.
Curiously,  cutting the music achieves the same ends for Tark that he
gets by <italic>not</italic>  cutting the images. Again T cannot bring
himself to editorialize, to enforce his choice.  T cannot bring himself
to employ music as emotional soundtrack, acknowledging that we should
no longer trust the simple relationships we have with culture/artists. 
Of course as always he would have his cake and eat it too, but clearly
the consumption is wrought with mistrust. 


Recalling that the original ending of <italic>Nostalghia</italic>  was
to have Gorchakov killed by a stray bullet from a terrorists gun and so
I quote form the Italian Terrorist Gianfranco Sanguinetti:


<paraindent><param>right,right,right,left,left,left</param>All acts of
terrorism, all the outrages which have struck and which strike the
imagination of men, have been and are either offensive actions or
defensive actions. If they form part of and offensive strategy,
experience has shown for a long time that they are always doomed to
fail. If, on the other hand, they form part of a defensive strategy,
experience shows that these acts can expect some success, which,
however is only momentary and precarious. (On Terrorism and the State
P57)

</paraindent>

When the anxiety of influence expands into a historical nightmare we
struggle to willfuly wake ourselves. At that liminal moment in between
dreaming and awakening having no control over the body can be the most
terrifying moment of all.


S





</x-rich>
