<< Obviously content and meaning are the important things, but don't dismiss
 entirely the value of a brief discussion of structure.  After all, Tarkovsky
 didn't psychically beam his ideas into our heads, he used sepcific actors,
 settings, and yes, even camerawork. >>

I agree with this wholheartedly--and in my intitial post I did try to make
this clear. Obviously one needs to talk about the work itself in order to talk
about meaning--my concern is when structure (etc.) becomes the alpha and omega
of a discussion. I'll talk tracking shots, long takes, jump cuts, dissolves,
and swish pans forever if I think it will amount to something. And certainly
Tarkovsky made some important technical and aesthetic decisions over the
years--long takes, use of sound, internal rhythm, etc.

<<But back to Nostalghia.  I have to agree somewhat with Aphrodite, I don't
think it's really a film about (certainly not for) women.  In many of his
films I keep seeing Parsifal, if you'll forgive me for getting a bit Jungian.
I keep seeing the wounded Fisher King, waiting for a holy fool to ask a
healing question.  This is a very male theme.  I keep thinking that if I pay
close enough attention to these films (except Solaris which I consider a
special case, more on that later) I'll find a map, one which will show me a
way to ... I'm not quite sure what.>>

Perhaps I overstated my case. It seems to me that this film deals more overtly
with women than any of Tark's other work (with the exception of Mirror). It
is, I agree, definitely not a woman's film, nor a film for women. I doubt
Tarkovsky could have ever made such a film. Perhaps I should say it is about
womanhood, or at least what Tarkovsky thinks womanhood should be. It is a male
take on women--but women are definitely a central theme, especially in their
roles as mothers.

If you'll allow me to put a Wagnerian spin on your Jungianism, I see more of
Tannhauser than Parzifal--though I do see what you mean. Here is G. suspended
between the ideal woman (his wife) and the ideal sexual woman (Eugenia). 

Remember, too, that my statement about the place of women in Nost. was made in
regards to connecting it to The Sacrifice which deals much more heavily with
men (esp. father and son). 

Thanks,

Seamus 

