Let me say that I agree with the spirit of your post and am all for open
dialogue etc., though it is important to remember that the infinite ways of
looking at a work could not possibly become manifest without disagreement.
Bickering, however, is another matter. And there has certainly been some of
that going on, though it has still been a good deal tamer than some of the
other discussions I have seen on this and other lists. 

However, as the self-appointed advocate of hermeneutics I feel obligated to
take issue with some of the other aspects of your post. 

One:

<<Isn't it necessary to consider, the concerned artist's expressed views on
why he create an object of art?>>

Frankly, no. Much has been written about the so-called "intentional fallacy"
over the years (see Roland Barthes and WK Wimsatt, in particular) and it has
been pretty well established that one need not have any concern or regard for
an artist's intentions, opinions, background, etc. Certainly, it is still AN
approach we can use, and not one that should be abandoned completely--but it
is also grounded in the idea that somehow an artist retains interpretive
ownership of a work. This simply isn't the case. Art is the property of those
who see it, etc. Moreover, the idea that an artist is responsible for CREATING
a work is also debatable--art like the artist is a product of society and of
other works (themselves products of the same). If we are to use the artist
him/herself as a point of reference then let's be honest: Tarkovsky is
responding to (rebelling against) the so-called Eisenstein aesthetic and is
largely informed by a Russian Orthodox background. Before Tarkovsky makes his
films he has been shaped by infinitely complex sources (the world) and after
the work is done those same sources (the world--infinitely changed) will
behold the work. Tarkovsky's own statements about his work are, ultimately,
nothing more than another interpretation of them.

<< When we are discussing a work of art to understand it, we should have the
 courage to see it from different angles and also not to overdo it beyond
 its own intentions and definitions.
  >>

I've never understood the idea that we should not "overdo it [interpretation]
beyond it [the work's] intentions and definitions." That's EXACTLY what we
should do. In fact, how could we do otherwise? And when exactly is one
"overdoing" it? As a literature major/student assistant I am consistently
hearing students complain of "overinterpretation." If an interpretation of a
work produces a beautiful or meaningful idea (and "beauty is truth, truth
beauty") then what difference does it make? What does it mean to understand a
work? And do we sincerely believe that the artist him or herself actually
understand the work? The work is felxible and can mean many things--so why
limit it? 

I, of course, love very much the two quotations that you select from
Tarkovsky--especially the one about the function of the artist being to
introuduce the capacity to love into the world. And I can honestly say that
his films have done this for me, among other things--but Tarkovsky also had
some very serious criticisms of society that he wished to introduce as well.
This, too, came from love. Love is not all agreement and communion--it is also
the desire and ability to be honest and to relish the complexity of the world.
In this list we have a miniature of that world and its complexity--but we are
limited to words and only words.

Ah, words. They are both our prisons and our means to freedom--as James Agee
wrote in an essay on photography:

"We are all so deeply caught in the tyranny of words, even where words are not
needed, that they have sometimes to be used as keys to unlock their own
handcuffs." 

Seamus


