Sarvenaz, you wrote:

<< I hadn't considered Wagner.  I hate to admit it, but I'm prejudiced against
 Wagner.  I know that personal predjudice is no excuse for ignoring something
 important.  Could you tell me more about Tannhauser pls.?  And before anybody
 attacks Tark for being a woman-hating pederast, let us all take a moment to
 recall that we each have both a male and a female aspect, and no human
 experience need be alien.>>
 
 >>

Wagner, for all his faults (and God knows he had plenty of them), is well
worth your time. If it helps: like Tarkovsky he repeatedly uses redemption
through love as a major motif. Tannhauser is about a young man who is torn
between love of one woman (the earthly, maidenly, pure, Elizabeth--I think
that was her name) and the well known beacon of erotica that is Venus. When he
is with Elizabeth he lusts for the goddess Venus and when he is with Venus he
longs for the woman Elizabeth. Talk about dialectic! There is much more, of
course, but that is the basic gist of it. He also composed an opera based on
Parzifal that has some beautiful music in it.

As per your discussion of Tark as masogynist--it is a touchy point. I think he
had some less than progressive ideas about the place of women in society, and
that some of those ideas are especially manifest in Nostalghia. While I would
not go so far as to call him woman-hating, or a pederast, or a masogynist, I
definitely sense some resentment of women's libbers, etc.

Are you a Jungian?--your allusion to the amima and animus priniciple would
seem to indicate so. . .
  
<<OK, Seamus, I'm going to go back and re-read those old posts before I jump
 back in again, but I'll be watching. >>

Hey, don't split on me. This is just getting good. You're last few posts have
been the main reason I haven't unsubscribed again.

