In a message dated 98-09-06 00:03:52 EDT, you write:

<<  And do we sincerely believe that the artist him or herself actually
 understand the work? >>

Anybody who writes, paints, composes, etc. will tell you that much of creation
is fortuitous.  Perhaps one takes note of an odd juxtaposition or perhaps one
takes dictation from one knows not quite where.  Certainly art is part lament
and part prophesy...

<< Tarkovsky also had some very serious criticisms of society that he wished
to introduce as well. This, too, came from love. Love is not all agreement and
communion--it is also the desire and ability to be honest and to relish the
complexity of the world.>>

I'm glad you brought up the issue of complexity and communion.  I  remember
seeing Solaris (my Tarkovsky virginity -- the first of his films that I saw)
and being very PROFOUNDLY affected.  I emphasize the word profound because for
the first time in my squirrely, voluble life, I was speechless.  I could
barely comprehend this new knowledge much less name it, yet there I was, naked
as Adam, scared and excited and brand new to the world.  

I was not OUTSIDE this film.  I didn't want to know what the director was
trying to say, I wanted to know what the ocean wanted, what Kelvin understood.
There he is, a man of science, a level head sent up there to find out what had
happened, restore order, make sense of it all, and what does he come to
understand?  Not his colleagues, the planet, or even his dead wife, but only
something in himself.  

I don't think I'm a Jungian in particular but certainly my aim is not to
debrief Tarkovsky's cinema with abstruse analyses so much as it is to uncover
the hidden maps that will lead me to someplace kind and peaceful within
myself.  Whenever I my head out of whack I think of Solaris and it sort of
puts things in perspective:  what it is ever possible to know about other
people directly (very little) and what it possible to know about them through
self-examination (a lot).

(I'll go intellectual again next time, Seamus, just had to get this out.  You
know, flattery will get you everywhere with me.)

