Scott:

>The defensiveness I was talking about was what I hear in the music,  in
>the strategies of creating music that indeed does reach the body (yes I
>agree) but only by a dis-orginisation/ re-orginization. (Artaud's body
>without organs  perhaps?) The corruptions in the direct relationships
>between mind, body, ear and instrument have become so noisy that some
>musicians resort to extreme methods to return to sensual pleasure. Don't
>get me wrong I like it. We don't have much choice left do we?

Sure, lots of choice, if we know where to start looking (the capitalist
distribution/marketing system is mainly what limits choice).

Don't you think that the main problem with commercial music (as well as
commercial cinema and TV) is that it fragments the self into these separate
targets, and mostly it's the appetites of the body that are being appealed
to (sensation, sensationalism, horror/gore/sex, "human interest"...)?

You don't need to destroy traditional musical values and structures
(rhythm, melody, harmony, texture, color etc.) to reinegrate the mind,
body, ear/instrument, and soul/emotion/spirit. In fact you'd better not
throw them out entirely, because they're what connects you to the domain of
music, and through it to other people.

Sometimes you hear defensiveness and protest, but I think the musicians who
are making a difference are on the offensive in this sense: they're
searching for and following their own muse, and often they're integrating
and extending not just their own (western) traditions, without prejudice of
"high"/classical or experimental  vs. "low" folk/popular culture, but also
what they find in musics from all over the world. At their best they're so
connected that they're free to improvise something of beauty and depth
together, one that includes the listener in a community which has never
existed before and will never exist in quite the same way again.

>Artists like these have a kind of mission that once was an assault on
>bourgeois taste but I don't see the term avant garde as appropriate due to
>the crumbling faith in community.  It suggests an uniformity in the ranks
>that can't be presumed anymore. I sort of think of these aesthetic
>assaults as "sorties" and more analogous to terrorists. But terrorism is
>only so if it is a public threat, and musicians cannot pose an aesthetic
>force without some kind of representation in numbers, a movement.  Hence
>my sense of futility.

I see your point but there are other factors involved. Music cultures used
to be determined more by gatekeepers than they are now. In the CD age it's
not that hard to get your music out there, though it's still hard to get it
heard widely. Thus there is no single "reactionary" avant-garde movement in
music; music is multifarious and fragmented (in a perhaps good, anarchic
sense).

Also avant-garde art depended on a concept of received, socially sanctioned
"high" art that seems a lot less compelling these days (except maybe in
reference to public obscenity in puritan-dominated societies like the US).
If avant art isn't a public threat is that because artists lack faith in
(their) community, or because we now realize the arts have never been able
to channel or represent a mass threat to power?

>
>In the closing scene of Nostalghia  the relationship between the images,
>music and our bodies is disrupted. The Ode to Joy  is "cut up" in the
>diegesis  - from within the scene. Curiously,  cutting the music achieves
>the same ends for Tark that he gets by not  cutting the images. Again T
>cannot bring himself to editorialize, to enforce his choice.  T cannot
>bring himself to employ music as emotional soundtrack, acknowledging that
>we should no longer trust the simple relationships we have with
>culture/artists.  Of course as always he would have his cake and eat it
>too, but clearly the consumption is wrought with mistrust.

Okay, but what about the final music in The Sacrifice (and some earlier
films)? It feels like an affirmation, even if not necessarily a simple one.
Maybe T is not trying to (underhandedly or otherwise) compel our agreement
through the power of music, but he is presenting his own statement of
memory/continuity, desire, and faith to us to take in in whatever way we
can.

>
>Recalling that the original ending of Nostalghia  was to have Gorchakov
>killed by a stray bullet from a terrorists gun and so I quote form the
>Italian Terrorist Gianfranco Sanguinetti:
>
>All acts of terrorism, all the outrages which have struck and which strike
>the imagination of men, have been and are either offensive actions or
>defensive actions. If they form part of and offensive strategy, experience
>has shown for a long time that they are always doomed to fail. If, on the
>other hand, they form part of a defensive strategy, experience shows that
>these acts can expect some success, which, however is only momentary and
>precarious. (On Terrorism and the State P57)
>
>When the anxiety of influence expands into a historical nightmare we
>struggle to willfuly wake ourselves. At that liminal moment in between
>dreaming and awakening having no control over the body can be the most
>terrifying moment of all.

Extending the phrase "anxiety of influence" into a new, totalizing social
context makes sense. Our bodies, as Foucault showed, are moulded by
society, nor is anything about us really our own beyond the particular
accidents of our genes and upbringing and the illusions of our will.
Terrorists of any kind are thus waging a losing battle against the alien
social structures they feel have been inscribed over who they "really" are,
and which they are nevertheless reinforcing both in themselves and in the
world. Defensive terrorism is still terrorism, it's all too willful, and
it's aimed at destroying rather than building community, isn't it (at least
community outside the terrorists' cell)? You can admire their guts
(sometimes) without agreeing with their aims or methods. (Sorry if this
sounds banal...)

So how to wrest some sense of self or certainty in this waking dream,
without succumbing to the illusion that individual control or sense of
identity can save us, much less society? This is where I think art, both
solitary, introspective creativity and group work/play, really does have a
role. It's why I'm here yakking with people I'll probably never meet. It's
what you said last week in your "Friends and Lovers" post:

>Is it so unatural to hope that we should do something with what we have
>taken from this filmaker? Perhaps he was a person we might have known, not
>a star of our projected ambition.  We needen't aspire to be famous or
>earth shattering --- simply creative in our own impenatrable private
>worlds -- that is the better part of being a "follower" no?

Though maybe not that impenetrable...

Tony


