Sarvenaz, you wrote: 

<< I was not OUTSIDE this film.  I didn't want to know what the director was
 trying to say, I wanted to know what the ocean wanted, what Kelvin
understood.
 There he is, a man of science, a level head sent up there to find out what
had
 happened, restore order, make sense of it all, and what does he come to
 understand?  Not his colleagues, the planet, or even his dead wife, but only
 something in himself.  
  >>

There is an interesting book called Cinema and Painting, or something like
that (I don't have it handy) that has a chapter on Tarkovsky's use of icon
painting in Andrei Rubilev. The aesthetics of Russian icon painting are
fascinating, especially when applied to cinema--something Tarkovsky was
apparently trying to do. What you describe above is an example of the aim of
icon painting--who arrange the very composition of the painting so that the
vanishing point is off the canvas (i.e. within the real world). I think that
this is Tarkovsky's aim with the long take: to blur the distance between the
world and the film. Moreover, in icon painting, there is no difference between
signifier and signified (to lapse into postmodern parlance for a moment)--a
figure is not represented in an icon painting. They are PRESENT. 

One former member of the list was convinced (and I agree) that Hari in Solaris
was essentially an icon. Interesting idea.

This is also reminiscent of Longinus' idea of the Sublime--but that I'll save
for another day. I get self-conscious if I pontificate too much.

Seamus

