I noticed that there is a poster of Nostalghia that features a scene that
is not in the film wherein Gorchakov is planting a big kiss on Eugenia.

I wonder if the marketing folks staged this scene or if it was ever
actaully in the film? A logical guess would be that if it is in the film it
probably took place early. It's easier for me to imagine that T would move
from sensuality to the acesticism. Having their passion appear late in the
film sort of implys that thats  what we've been waiting for and that's what
its all been about.  Yet I could see that it could appear then dissapear
quickly enough -- easily dismissed by Gorchakov as a mistake. Who knows how
T would play it.

One hint would be that when Eugenia is about to leave she tells Gorchacov
that he was "almost unfaithful" to his wife. This might mean that such a
moment had occured between them. If so the only place that seems to work to
me in the film would be very early, in fact I'd say in a second scene after
the visit to the church and before we see them waiting in the hotel lobby
at Bagno Vignone. Placing it between any two scenes after that looks
impractical... of course who knows what else may have been removed that may
have been in the original script. The only way that I see it fitting in
later would be if it appeared in one of Gorchacov's dreams but never took
place between the two characters.

Has anyone ever seen a script of Nostalghia? Of course even if the scene is
not in the script it still may have  developed on the set.

For my part I don't think it is needed in the film, so if it was removed I
understand why. We can see there's amourous tension between them so the
only reason to have it would be to make that more palpable, and such
gestures of sexual sensuality would throw the aesthetics out of balance.

S



