Sarvenaz wrote:

<< his is what I find most seductive about
 Tarkovsky's cinema:  those excruciatingly, lasciviously long takes with no
 immediadte gratification, no rapid catharsis.  Can anybody recommend other
 pictures with this quality?  (except Kourismaki, though I liked "Ariel") And
 did everybody hear that Kurosawa died?  A moment of silence...
  >>

Though I don't think it works as well Sokurov (sometimes called Tark's
protege) uses silence a great deal--almost exclusively (Mother and Son). I
would recommend any film by Yasujiro Ozu--especially Autumn Afternoon and
Tokyo Story. While his takes are not as long as Tarkovsky's, they share that
same meditative quality you are describing here. And silence is ever so
important. Scenes in Ozu's films are like a series of haikus. Mike Leigh has
recently moved towards the long take, though with more of a realist's interest
in documenting relationships than Tark or the aforementioned directors--still,
great stuff.

Seamus 
