<x-rich>

<paraindent><param>right,right,right,right,left,left,left,left</param>>
Scott,about the paints in the background,it's hard to have just one 

>approach.Some people understood it coud be a kind of action of the 

>ocean,that was reading Kris' deep thoughts.

</paraindent>


Rey


I can see that.  That is certainly one reason why Tarkovsky had those
paintings hung there, to serve as a reading of Kris. Thinking about
this makes me think of Solaris as Tarkovsky  himself! He is like any
author/creator who begins with a central character then builds the
surrounding society in a way to express something about that
character.


What you are saying comes across best I think in the scene where Kris
finds Hari lost in thought staring at "Hunters in the Snow".  I see
this as an action of the ocean because it seems to me that Hari
<italic>ultimately is Solaris herself</italic>,  blossoming in the
benevolence of Kris' kind projection. As time goes on Solaris is
understanding Kris -- and humanity -- more and more.


A theme I see a lot in T is how closely connected humans can be to one
another, how they overlap. In spite of the sort of pessimistic thought
that we only seek ourselves "out there" -- that we project our own
objects of love and hate upon one another -- here is an example of how
a projection (Kris' Hari) upon another being (Solaris' Hari) produces 
a "visitor" who apparently achieves a greater conscious development
than any of the previous "visiting" incarnations.  


Kris' powers of creation has become as impressive as Solaris'.  This
phenomenon is not science fiction.


"How wonderful!" 


S
