<< Sorry, Tarden, but there is not too short a characterization when
 speaking of Ozu to say simply that his films are like a series of haikus?
 And what about the goolash-like films of Istvan Szabo?
  >>

Fair enough. I could, frankly, speak of Ozu with intense fondness and
admiration for about ten years only stopping to renew my breath. Remember: I
was recommending other director's, not doing my usual by putting the "anal"
back in analysis. Still, as I said, fair enough:

Some people complain that Ozu's shots are too static and standardized. Most
takes last a minute/minute and a half or so and feature little or no movement
(unlike Tark with his tracking shots). Moreover, the camera is almost
constantly set at three feet above the ground. One of my favorite Ozu moments
is in Autumn Afternoon. The father of the story works in an office. After some
beautiful (and, yes, haiku-like) establishing shots,  30 second Ozu shot set
in the hallway outside the office shows a secretary walk by. We then see the
father in his office sifting through a stack of paperwork. Later on in the
film the series of shots is duplicated, but very subtly, giving the gradual
impression that the film has started over again--and, also, that the
character's life is tedious and repetitious.  

When I say that the shots are like haikus, I mean that like haikus they are
deceptively simple. The point of a haiku is to, without gimmickery, capture
the essence of a moment. One famous addage used by Basho or Buson (maybe
another celebrated haiku writer) is that a haiku is like a finger pointing at
the moon, if the finger is covered with rings and jewels it distracts from the
moon. Ozu does this for me: he is never melodramatic, not even close. He never
uses the camera in ways that draw attention to the camera itself. Orson Welles
once said that Vittorio de Sica (I think he was referring to Shoeshine in
particular) could do the one thing with a camera that he himself could not do:
make you forget it was there. This is true of Ozu, as well. His camera is not
cold or dispassionate, it is simply unintrusive. I suppose that Joyce's notion
of "symapthetic detachment" best describes what I mean. Like Chekhov, Ozu
gives each character all the love and attention they deserve--too many
directors save their love for the technique of filmmaking.

As per Szabo's goolash-like films--This, too, is too short of a
characterization! (I suppose you were sort of poking fun at me . . . again,
fair enough) But now it's your turn to expand on what you mean. I, for one,
have not seen any Szabo and cannot say--though I have heard that several
Hungarian directors have experimented with unbelievably long takes.

Seamus  
