<< I tried showing Nostalghia to a well-educated (loves Cocteau's Beauty and
 the Beast and Orpheus and Antonnioni's La'Ventura and Fellinni's La
 Strada) art friend the other day.  She found it heavy-handed,
 self-serving and so intrusively autobiographical that it interferred with
 her willing suspension of disbelief.   >>

I've been thinking about this and think that there is some truth in your
friend's observation. There is a preachiness about Tarkovsky that can be
intrusive--I have always grappled with these weaknesses since Nostalghia and
The Sacrifice are both my favorite films by Tark and also his most openly
opinionated work. Holding to the aesthetic that Realism and Joyce's
"sympathetic detachment" (which I have somethow managed to mention twice in
one day), that is, some sort of artlessness, are the ideal, I think that
Tarkovsky has some problems. But I am not as convinced as I once was that this
aesthetic ideal is necessarily to be worshipped. There are some great artists
who break this very rule almost incessantly--Dostoevsky, Celine, Proust,
Rimbaud . . . There are times when an artist's consciousness is what appeals
to us as much as their craftmanship--that is, that sometimes it is what a
person says about the world that is more important or beautiful than their
abilityto re-create it. And yet, Tarkovsky is also a master-craftsman in his
camerwork, etc . . .

So there must be another distinction. Perhaps it is characterization. In the
later films I find that Tark's psychology is stronger than his
characterization. I hope I can make this distinction clear: Tark probes minds
well, but there is more to people than their moods--and so much is left
unexplored. Again, I think of Dostoevsky--so often his characters are best
seen as aspects of one greater mind. The brothers in Bros K, for instance,
have always struck me as aspects of a mind that Dost is analyzing: the
intellectual, the hedonist, the faithful one, the repressed Evil One . . .
Perhaps there is something like this in Nostalghia and The Sacrifice (even
Stalker . . .)

Tarkovsky seems to have carved out a very select philosophical/psychological
area for himself--one that cannot be judged fairly by the old art for art's
sake aesthetic. He is honest in placing himself within the work itself, in
openly expressing opinions and placing them within the mouth's of his
characters. And yet, somehow, he makes it work.

Seamus 
