I think that in general Tarkovsky works in an iconographic way.  He seems
to be interested in the  Platonic notion that things in this world are
smaller models of ideal things somewhere beyond.  These things are not
symbols.  They are copies of ideal prototypes and they participate in the
nature of these prototypes.  I really need to read Plato more carefully
than I have; I'm probably not expressing him very clearly.  Hari is his
most explicit example of this principle, but one can see it working
throughout his work.  In Mirror, the house and the mother and the wife. 
In Sacrifice, there is Little Man's model.  In Nostalghia Domenico and
Andrei are actually united in a Eucharistic way,  Andrei partaking of
Domenico's essence, becoming one with him.

When people write icons they actually work from a prototypical icon,
tracing off it to try to minimize innovation.  Well, gotta go.  Thomas

