Hi Thomas,
Well, I didn't mean to insult you, so your reaction is a bit exaggerated.
Let me explain what I meant: Platonic ideal is something quite definite. For
example, take the notion of triangle. All the possible (or "physical")
triangles in the world have something in common, which is their "trianglity"
if I may say so. THIS is the ideal of triangle, more or less. Now if you
take this notion and use it on people you obviously should be careful. There
is a Platonic ideal of human being, but only a general one. There are not
many such ideals or prototypes and there are not personal or individual ideals.
I don't have any problem with what you wrote about Hari as a copy of Kris's
old girlfriend who is also some sort of embodiment of the planet. I just
felt very uneasy with using Plato as a source for explanation (you don't
have to agree with me of course, but certainly YOU are the one to explain or
give examples - only if you like, I mean - and not me, as you demand. After
all you are the one who made a claim. I just didn't agree.

>In Thomas' defense, I don't think he was name-dropping.
>Really, I think this crowd could get a lot more obscure than PLATO fer
>chrissakes if we wanted to show off.
>Sarvenaz
 
Sarvenaz, I didn't mean to say that Thomas is a name-dropper, but using BIG
names instead of explaining explicitly what you mean using your own words
opens the way for such an attitude. Personally I think it's not healthy.
Again, nobody should agree with me, but - I hope - it's legitimate to
criticize without getting into personal insults, as Thomas (and Seamus?)
did. And by the way, folks, the idea that Plato supported dictatorship (with
good reasoning in his openion) is not my idea but a common knowledge which
can easily be checkecd by anybody interested. Just open some books in
philosophy and look for Plato's ideas on state. Since he thought that the
state stands higher than the individual, I see his idea as facist, again as
a fact, not meaning to insult (Plato).

