	Given the renewed interest - and even pasions- in platonism, I go
to post something on the relationship between platonic Ideas and 
things/persons in the world. Although not explicitly tarko, there may be 
some remote connection.
	The problem is "participatio": firstly we have the world of
phaenomena, that we inhabit in a sensual way. Secondly, the platonic
line of thought lead us to accept the realm of Ideas. In what concerns
thinking, it seems as if we live here. The problem of the reality -
whatever this may mean- of this or that world rests somehow on their
mutual relationship.
	Platonicly, the Ideas world is the more real. The phaenomenal
world gets reality inasmuch it is a reflection of the ideal upthere. The
World in itself is a humble reality and the soul should avoid mixing up
with it. But as a reflection - even through a glass- of the Ideas, the
world becomes worth considering. This may be so, for the soul is
encapsulated in the world and its concern is to get out of here. We
may think of the ideal realm as some natural place where the soul wants to
stay. As now, by reflecting Ideas, the world gets some transparence and a
road out may apear. Platonism is nostalgy ( pain of geting back).
	Some primitives hold that the world undergoes a continuous
disruption. The man should take its part in the restoration of the world.
This happens periodically. In "reality" this restoration is a creation ab
initio of the world. Maybe a new creation, from time to time? No, every
creation is nothing but the first one, that was out-of-time. This pattern
of thinking is platonic, and men get "really" into that time-without-time,
where the world may be an Idea at most.
	It seems to me that the incarnation of the Christ may be also 
taken as a relationship between the two realms. The Word comes into the
world. Although I can not elaborate on this, it seemed to me necesary to
point this out.
	One can easily find other relation mechanisms in the history of
ideas. Though it seems that none is so simple to reduce just to a scale
transformation. But then what to do with scale models in T's films? Should
they be copies of ideas? Or they should simply point out that beside the
world as we know it there IS a world of Ideas? That is, ideas have a
reality in themselves, they are not nothing. Or may it be simply that
Tarkovski loved cute little things and was so sympathetic towards them as
to put them in the film?
	
attila

	I do not know Plato or the platonists, but the concept of
platonism is so freely and widely used that it seems unavoidable. That is,
you may discard it but then you have to invent it again. Besides, its
archetipal content makes it very pleasant. So I apologize to all those
persons who use this concepts in an exact fashion.
