Haim:

We all seem to have gotten off on the wrong foot. The fact that the postings I
read this morning were the most consistently interesting in months is more
than enough to convince to be a bit repentant at having possibly been
defensive, etc.

You write:

<<Again, nobody should agree with me, but - I hope - it's legitimate to
criticize without getting into personal insults, as Thomas (and Seamus?)
did.>>

Though it causes me indescribable grief to admit (without qualification) that
it is legitimate to criticize my ideas and attempts at expressing those ideas,
I do so openly. Sigh.And I suppose I did slip into personal insults by
agreeing with Thomas'  comparing Haim to Harm Snell (an old member of the
list), so I'll own up to that. 

Haim's criticisms, however, are not without reproach:

<< So, it may be interesting to show some resemblance between, let's say T and
 Platonic ideas or Ozu and Haiku poems, but if it's not backed by convincing
 examples or other kind of strengthening, it's not worth too much and anybody
 can easily throw "important" names in the air; it sounds very impressive,
 but what really does it worth?! >>

This is not much of an objection. To simply say that something is not
convincing is, itself, not convincing. What didn't convince you? I will stick
to the haiku example since it was mine and I am most responsible for it. In my
initial post comparing Ozu's cinematic rhythm to that of a series of haikus I
was DESCRIBING a director's style to another member of the list who was
interested in other directors who use long takes and/or silence in the their
films. As the old saying goes "Talking about music is like dancing about
architecture." The same is true of film--I can write until my fingers are
bleeding all over the keyboard and not be any closer to describing a film
accurately to someone who hasn't seen it. So, predictably, there was a degree
of failure in my description. When asked to elaborate, I did. I described
(with a supporting addage) the aesthetic of haiku poetry and then gave a rough
account of Ozu's own aesthetic by recounting a particular duo of scenes.
Apparently this was equally unconvincing. So it goes. However, if a criticism
is to be levied against my point, then something must be said that is
critical--which I distinguish from contradictory or contrary.

Instead I have been told that my idea is merely "interesting"--an odd
complaint, if I may say so. At the same time my idea is seen as impressive
sounding and, ultimately, worthless. I found that my idea (and or Thomas') was
so worthless that it actually required double punctuation to get across the
full degree of indignation ("?!")

But I'm getting snooty--not my aim. My point is this: Criticism should be
taken seriously when it has substance. The above quoted bit of criticism seems
to me to be little more than a veiled form of attack. I have attempted to take
it seriously anyhow. 

I'm still waiting to hear about Szabo and his goolash-like cinema. I'm
genuinely intrigued . . .
 
As I said, this morning I discovered a wonderful exchange between Haim and
Sarvenaz that seemed to me well thought out--I hope that this will be the
precedent that all of us follow. The point of this group is discussion--which
implies a certain amount of arguing. Good. 


Now, let's get on with something more interesting.

Seamus
