First of all, I'm sorry I overreacted, taking offense and giving it in
return. I apologize.  Back in the late spring on the list, I was called a
fascist and a jew lover and told I had nothing worth saying.  The asshole
would post one sentence pooh poohs on everyone's hard work.  For a
misguided moment I thought that person had returned.  I am truly sorry.  


Everyone has said everything very well.  Farkas summarized what little I
know about Platonism very well.  Tarden with quotes and explanation
explained well most of what I was trying to say.  I must say that the
discussion has taken a dramatic turn up in intensity and I love it.  I've
started saving messages again, trying to maintain thought streams between
people.

I agree with the general tenor of Haim's view of Plato's politics.  They
creep me out so much that I keep putting Plato down when I should be
reading him.  I especially don't like his view of poets (being a poet
myself) and censorship (he's all for it).  However, fascism is a much
latter movement historically, and I doubt it has much at all to do with
Plato though I'm not sure.   I am fascinated that Hitler gave Mussolini
Nietzsche's  Power of the Will.  I'm also fascinated with one of
Mussolini definitions of Fascism:  Fascism is rule by the corporation. 
To me that speaks vols. about where the U.S. and it's spawn (i.e.
corporations) are headed.  But enough politics.

Anyway, I associate Tarkovsky with Plato primarily because of Nostalghia.
 Something Farkas just said makes the connection even stronger for me: 
	the soul is encapsulated in the world and its concern is to get
out of here. 	We may think of the ideal realm as some natural
place where the soul 		wants to stay. As now, by reflecting
Ideas, the world gets some 		transparence and a road out
may appear. Platonism is nostalgia ( pain of 	getting back)."
Because Plato taught the pre-existence of the soul it makes sense (in
that cosmology) that the soul could be nostalgic for it's true home. 
This seems to be what Tark is getting at in Nostalghia what with the 1
+1=1, the Russian home inside the church and the snow as a depiction of
Andrei's death.  For a guy who despises symbols, Tark lays 'em on pretty
thick in that film.

What I was saying about Hari and the model houses I meant to be taken on
a metanomic (metaphical) level.  Of course, Tark was not dealing in
Ideals and their earthly copies literally.  I was just trying to say that
all this semiotic (copy of a copy of copy) seemed metanomicly evocative
of certain Platonic ideas which we know from Sculpting and Nostalghia
that Tark had a fondness for.

Also, I happen to know, as an Eastern Orthodox, that Orthodox folks tend
to prefer Plato over Aristotle and the rest.  The Orthodox intellectuals
I know all write dissertations on Plato, etc.  Personally, I haven't read
much of the Old Greek, but as an "intellectual" who converted a number of
years ago from Western Christianity, I'm always getting Plato put on my
plate so to speak.  I also end up hearing many  "In praise of Plato"
conversations.  Santayanna once said, "I'm so stupid I'm almost a poet." 
Well, I am a poet!"  I can only work with image and metaphor---anything
abstract and I get lost.  However, when I started watching this Russian
Orthodox film maker, I expected to find and did find plenty of Plato
there.  If you compare what Farkas wrote with the Timothy Ware (he
definitely gets the Orthodox Housekeeping seal of approval) quotes on
iconography that Tarden (an athiest quoting my guys, what's the world
coming to) provided, you will see the similarity in world view.  In fact,
it is a common accusation that Eastern Orthodoxy is merely warmed over
Platonism and neo-Platonism.  However, not being a theologian I'm not
sure I can respond to that accusation.  Cheers  Thomas

