Scott Rhodes wrote:

> Or maybe that famous scene in Brooks' In Cold Blood wherein Robert Blake's character tells the story of his father's death as he stands at a window watching the rain outside. Though he never sheds a tear the shadow of the rain dripping down the window pain is projected onto his face creating a ghostly marraige of the external with the deepest internal. That shot was not planned that way, that was nature's doing.

Can you please explain what you mean by nature's doing?  I agree with you that this specific shot was not initially planned that way, but the cinematographer, Conrad Hall, after having placed his key light to shine through the rain-machine splattered window, noticed the effect on Blake's face and brought it to Brook's attention (they may have even shot a take before the effect was noticed, but I can't remember).
With Brook's ok, Hall went back and tweaked the lights to make the effect more pronounced. It was a simple situation of an attentive professional/artisan taking advantage of a "beautiful accident" (Haskell Wexler's term for such moments), recognizing that it would serve the subtext of the scene, and ultimately "creating a ghostly marriage of the external with the deepest internal." Though these lucky accidents are
always appreciated when they happen, it still takes a professional with extensive knowledge and experience to recognize and employ and manipulate all the necessary elements to their desired fruition.

Reichart
