>And Mussolini started the first ever film festival in Venice!!

</paraindent>

Sunny 


Yes Syberberg I've wanted to see that for years! 


May I ask where you saw it? Did you find any relationship to Tark ... 
although  I understand it has an impersonal style it's supposed to be
pretty melancholic and maybe even obliquely autobiographical about
Syberberg himself?



As an 'explaination' of Hitler much has been written about his trauma
during WW1 and his childhood. Tark's formative experiences are
similar... though T is diametrically opposed to Hitler, it seems to me,
in the sense that the bellicose choose to act on their projected
ideals... hero, enemies, nationality, etc. 


In all of the discussion of T's concern with ideals T was VERY
ambivalent about ideals. The miniatures in Nost belonged to a crazy
man, who presumably would have subjected his family to such
constrictions if he could.  In Sacrifice when Alexander finds the model
of his dream home he is clearly frightened. Quoting the line from
Macbeth suggests fear, guilt and betrayal. Some how the act of Little
Man building this model for his father is less than pleasing to Alex.
Furthermore the ideal home that he and his wife were captivated by was
soon to be toast.


One distinction seems worth mentioning. T appears to have a great deal
of respect for nature, the disparaged 'copys' I mentioned are all man
made. And even religion seems to fall into this category of ambivalence
(granted, it's a complex subject Thomas!) But it's questionable whether
or not<italic> natural objects </italic> are "copies" in T's scheme. No
demiurge to blame? So perhaps his films are not Platonist, nor Gnostic 
-- but not exactly humanist either.



S


