<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>>Scott Rhodes wrote:

</paraindent><paraindent><param>right,right,right,right,left,left,left,left</param>

>> Or maybe that famous scene in Brooks' In Cold Blood wherein Robert
Blake's character tells the story of his father's death as he stands at
a window watching the rain outside. Though he never sheds a tear the
shadow of the rain dripping down the window pain is projected onto his
face creating a ghostly marraige of the external with the deepest
internal. That shot was not planned that way, that was nature's doing.

</paraindent><paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

>Can you please explain what you mean by nature's doing?  I agree with
you that this specific shot was not initially planned that way, but the
cinematographer, Conrad Hall, after having placed his key light to
shine through the rain-machine splattered window, noticed the effect on
Blake's face and brought it to Brook's attention (they may have even
shot a take before the effect was noticed, but I can't remember).

>With Brook's ok, Hall went back and tweaked the lights to make the
effect more pronounced. It was a simple situation of an attentive
professional/artisan taking advantage of a "beautiful accident"
(Haskell Wexler's term for such moments), recognizing that it would
serve the subtext of the scene, and ultimately "creating a ghostly
marriage of the external with the deepest internal." Though these lucky
accidents are

>always appreciated when they happen, it still takes a professional
with extensive knowledge and experience to recognize and employ and
manipulate all the necessary elements to their desired fruition.


>Reichart

</paraindent>

Hey Reichart


Thanks for filling in the gaps in the story.


This reminds me of the time I attended a workshop with Stan Brakhage
wherein he spent a great deal of time talking about all kinds of things
like "closed eye visions", his relationship with the muse and what it
was like to be a mountain man during the beat generation. Of course I
loved every minute of it but having established all that I wanted to
ask him for some insight into the problem of dealing with the
<italic>bazillion  </italic>technical distractions  -- those logistics
of being on a film set that so easily drown the subtle voices of
inspiration. 


<paraindent><param>right,left</param>"How do we leave ourselves open
enough to allow the muse..."


"Allow...?" He interrupted "<italic>Allow...?"

</italic></paraindent><italic>

</italic>He then went on for another long time explaining that the muse
is not at our disposal, that the muse is like the "Prom Queen who casts
a glance our way if she sees fit." 


Fair enough. I suppose its sort of misguided to ask for sensible advice
from a guy who claims to work in a trance. 


Like I said, this notion is difficult for me to understand and convey
in my modern mind. I think it has to do with the fact that this state
of mind, this disposition toward the world is so easily crushed that
those whose livelyhood depends on it are reluctant to mess with it.
Also you just can't beat that "eurika " experience of self discovery so
it shouldn't be pre-emted. In My opinion, its easier for poets who work
alone to stay quiet, but in a collaborative medium like film we are
face with finding ways to talk to those we work for.


I guess we could safely say that nature conspired in this creative act.
 Hall's vigilance on the set was exemplary. Yes you are right that it
is a<italic> simple</italic>  situation of an attentive
professional/artisan taking advantage of a 'beautiful accident' -- this
one would have been difficult to miss in the eye piece I suppose. But
it's a good illustration of how life seems to tap into our themes, help
us out, don't you think?


Over and over T conveys the idea that showing up for work with a
preconception is no way to create art. He even goes on to say that the
artist has to get out of the way. I like to think that it's consistent
with this to disregard the whole notion of "unconscious" origins of an
artist's creations and imagine that all these things come from outside
us, we are <italic>inspired</italic>  in the original sense of the
word. 


You probably see what I'm getting at here. I hope I haven't over
simplified things, none of this sounds very impressive until it happens
to us. As a matter of fact it just sounds silly. But these are the
things that make our day, no matter what kind of work we do. Maybe it's
what we live for. It's sort of a religious idea but wasn't it nice when
we used to <italic>know </italic>that the stars corresponded to the
body, that we were <italic>at home  </italic>in the universe? 


Of course it also made us feel more uniquely vulnerable and paranoid
but that's another matter....


S



 

</x-rich>
