  >>

Yeah, the haiku thing was really for descriptive purpose more than anything.
You're right about the lengthiness of course--and haikus are anything but
lengthy. I was thinking more of the apparently simplicity of both.
Whatever--it's really not that important. I'm glad all of this has been ironed
out and that we can move on with a better understanding of each other's
methods, etc. And anyhow: not all of us have time to sit around writing full
formulated theses.

Water in Tarkovsky: this question was broached recently by Sarvenaz.
Oftentimes (and I think the Tarkmeister himself mentions this in SWT) water is
emblematic of time passing in his films. Consider, for instance, the stopped
clock in the jar of water in Mirror--one of the shots that Tark considered
overtly symbolic. I think, too, that this is why water is so often associated
with decay and detritus (Stalker, Mirror, Nostalghia)--time wears down the
physical world. Oftentimes, money and weaponry are seen immersed in
water--Tark's comment on the temporality of such things.

But this idea breaks down when one notes the presence of art within these
pools as well (in particular the van eyck painting in Stalker). On the whole,
I think that tark's use of water is as fluid as water itself. Tark, of course,
denies the use of emblems in his films--not very convincing, but worth noting.

Nostalghia is particularly water logged (the Petrie book makes this
observation). I have no idea if one meaning could be assigned to water in this
particular film. I doubt it.

Some time ago there was an attempt at compiling (her on this discussion group)
a sort of concordance of various repeat symbols in Tark's films: horses, dogs,
milk, water, and so on. At that time I posted on what i called "levitation for
love" using an article from SIght and SOund as my basis. IN that article Tark
was quoted as asking someone (while making the Sacrifice) which director had
best reproduced the sensation of being in love on screen. He quickly answered
that it was himself, in MIrror, when we see the mother levitating above the
bed, the husband beside her. Levitation, Tark suggested, best captured the
unreal floating sensation of love. He used it, then, once more in The
Sacrifice--Alexander and Maria (the witch) floating above the bed.

But I think that it is a dominant motif in Tark's films. If anyone has my
original post (Scott? Thomas?) I'd like to see it re-posted (it has better
documentation than my current ramblings). Here, though, is a rough paraphrase
of my idea:

Ivan's Childhood: the scene where the soldier kisses the other (female)
soldier in the woods, his legs on either side of a ditch, holding her in mid-
air. This is interesting since he is not in love, but she is. She is floating
but he is not--and he is the one holding her up (leading her on).

Andrei Rubilev: the opening scene with the peasant flying in the makeshift
balloon--a bit of a stretch, but worth mentioning.

Solaris: An easy one: the 30 seconds of weightlessness between Hari and Kelvin
as they dance the waltz of love through mid-air. (sigh)

Mirror: (already explained)

Stalker: the big hole in my theory. Any ideas--I can't think of a single
goddamned thing.

Nostalghia: the daydream image of G's wife, pregnant, and floating in space on
the bed--one of my favorite shots in all of tarkovsky.

The Sacrifice: (already explained)

Any Ideas?

And yes, "happy new year" or, as my younger sister used to say as she was
learing to talk: "happy new you!"

Seamus      
