Scott Rhodes wrote:


> This reminds me of the time I attended a workshop with Stan Brakhage wherein he spent a great deal of time talking about all kinds of things like "closed eye visions", his relationship with the muse and what it was like to be a mountain man during the beat generation. Of course I loved every minute of it but having established all that I wanted to ask him for some insight into the problem of dealing with the bazillion technical distractions -- those logistics of being on a film set that so easily drown the subtle voices of inspiration.
>
> "How do we leave ourselves open enough to allow the muse..."
>
> "Allow...?" He interrupted "Allow...?"
>
> He then went on for another long time explaining that the muse is not at our disposal, that the muse is like the "Prom Queen who casts a glance our way if she sees fit."
>
> Fair enough. I suppose its sort of misguided to ask for sensible advice from a guy who claims to work in a trance.
>
> Like I said, this notion is difficult for me to understand and convey in my modern mind. I think it has to do with the fact that this state of mind, this disposition toward the world is so easily crushed that those whose livelyhood depends on it are reluctant to mess with it.

> Also you just can't beat that "eurika " experience of self discovery so it shouldn't be pre-emted.

What if one morning an Azande tribesman had opened his eyes and woken up to "energy is equal to mass times the speed of light squared?"  Would he have gone out and killed a chicken to expose the culprit of such bewitching nonsense, or would he have shrugged his shoulders and gone back to sleep?  Or would he have locked himself up in a room, turned his back to the definitions and expectations placed upon him by his society, and spent a lifetime attempting to decipher it -- obsessed with this singular vision...'building a series of tiny
metal fishes' like in Garcia Marquez's A HUNDRED YEARS OF SOLITUDE?

In one degree or another, we are all inspired; I think it is just a function of our abilities and experiences and insights that determines how far we are able to elaborate and build upon our litany of inspired moments -- this is what separates the truly gifted from the merely inspired.

"...the problem of dealing with the bazillion technical distractions -- those logistics of being on a film set that so easily drown the subtle voices of inspiration." The more technically proficient you are the less of the need to concentrate on such matters and the more you can delve and focus on what is at the heart of your aesthetic search; and in certain cases, where the modes of expression are insufficient or have been exhausted, a good grounding in technique may enable you to have the resources to create a new language, a new
technique, a repostulating on the way to see and hear,  so as to ultimately communicate as fully as possible what is inside of us.

So, yes... the muse is like the "Prom Queen who casts a glance our way if she sees fit." But only a few of us will have the courage and ability to ask her to dance, and succeed; and fewer still, at the end of the night when the festivities are over, will be able to take her to a hotel (in the back of a car; home; forest; alleyway; wherever...) and bang the hell outta her.


> In My opinion, its easier for poets who work alone to stay quiet,

It is the nature of all who work alone...and yet,  if we peered inside the mind of a poet wouldn't we be bombarded by an effusion of questions, doubts, shouting matches, and diatribes about the process of creation...not unlike the chaotic nature of some movie sets?

> but in a collaborative medium like film we are face with finding ways to talk to those we work for.

Yes, as far as communicating what we want and expect of our collaborators, and finding a clarity  and specificity in the expression of the desired elements, but it still doesn't mean nor does it require that we reveal our motives or explain ourselves...our choices can and do sometimes remain a mystery to our collaborators (and sometimes to ourselves).

>  I guess we could safely say that nature conspired in this creative act. Hall's vigilance on the set was exemplary. Yes you are right that it is a simple situation of an attentive professional/artisan taking advantage of a 'beautiful accident' -- this one would have been difficult to miss in the eye piece I suppose. But it's a good illustration of how life seems to tap into our themes, help us out, don't you think?
>
> Over and over T conveys the idea that showing up for work with a preconception is no way to create art.

And yet, as is shown in DIRECTED BY ANDREI TARKOVSKY, he often works from preconceived elements and is angered when certain pre-arranged details haven't been carried out to his satisfaction or expectations (i.e.. see the lashing Anna Asp gets for not delivering the goods.)  Furthermore, the fact that he has agreed to a certain color scheme, the casting of specific individuals, choice of location, set construct, b&w or color, etc., is all a process of preconception. And what are we to make about particularly complex shots that require a
lot of preplanning?

Cinema is after all an amalgamation of different disciplines, all of them intertwined, sometimes in support and sometimes at odds with one another, but ultimately all employed in the construct of some Truth.

 Also, as we all know, Tarkovksy was operating from a very specific aesthetic ideology and infused all his decisions, whether planned months ago or at a moments notice, with his prejudiced convictions.

> He even goes on to say that the artist has to get out of the way. I like to think that it's consistent with this to disregard the whole notion of "unconscious" origins of an artist's creations and imagine that all these things come from outside us, we are inspired in the original sense of the word.

I don't agree. After all, Tark 's films are not a function of indeterminacy or Chaos Theory or algorithmic formulas...etc.; rather they are a construct of the artistic interplay of temperament and context -- this symbiotic relationship sometimes gives precedence to the artist  in allowing him to exert his will and overriding influence on his surroundings, and at other times it is the external forces that allow the artist to step back and react.  A fugue...

And, as is so obvious by Tark's employment of repeating motifs and obsessions throughout his films, Tark rarely got "out of the way."


>  You probably see what I'm getting at here. I hope I haven't over simplified things, none of this sounds very impressive until it happens to us. As a matter of fact it just sounds silly. But these are the things that make our day, no matter what kind of work we do. Maybe it's what we live for.



> It's sort of a religious idea but wasn't it nice when we used to know that the stars corresponded to the body, that we were at home in the universe?

"...used to know..."???  We are all carbon based beings; we carry the origins of the stars inside of us. We are the universe.

Reichart

