<< The discussion upon water created a need for me to send
 my two bits.  In Sacrifice Tark. gives us a scenes that water and the
 earth being trudged through.  In the reflection of the water the viewer
 sees the reflection ofthe sky. This idea of water, earth(ground) and sky
 in harmony relates to the Ikabon tree that is spoken of throughout the
 film.  In the Ikabon following it is believed that one becomes whole when
 these three elements are in balance which leads me to believe that it is
 significant to The Sacrifice.  Other items also relate to this, the robe
 thatisworn has a yin yang on the back as well as the eastern music that is
 incorporated within the work.  >>

Yes, I have always been intrigued that Eastern modes of thought seem to take
over toward the end of the film--or at least around the period of the
sacrificial burning of the house. Not only the shakuhachi music and the taoist
robe, but the entire landscape suddenly begins to resemble the waterlogged
rice fields of Asia. Alexander even takes a zen-like meditative pose at he
watches the house burn down. Your idea of the merging of the three elements
(really all four if you included the, later, burning down of the house) is
very convincing.

Here's something I've always wanted to mention and just remembered to: when
Alexander's wife sits down, in grief, to watch the home burn down she assumes
a very interesting pose. She is beside a puddle with her legs to one side and
leaning on her elbow (something like that). I remember seeing The Sacrifice in
the theatre with a friend--it was the first time either of us had seen the
film since going to see Nostalghia (twice in a row) a month or so earlier. As
we sat there, watching her laying there we both suddenly gasped. The shot was
a reversal (that is, shot from behind) of the final shot of Gorchakov in
Nostalghia as he assumes an identical pose (beside a puddle) facing the
audience, his home behind him. In Nostalghia, of course, the home has (in a
sense) been restored (via the death of the character). In The Sacrifice the
life of the character(s) is restored via the destruction of the house. This
seems to me to further link these two films in an interesting way . . . but
I'm still at a loss as to what the meaning might be.

Another interesting thing about that shot of her watching the house: if you
pay close attention you can catch a match cut. That is, what tark apparently
did was have the actress (Fleetwood?) sit very still until the house collapsed
from frame and then cut out much of the interim while still making the shot
look continuous. I didn't even notice the slight shift until I'd seen the film
for billionth time or whatever it was. I'd always wondered how Tark got the
house to collapse on cue.

Yes, also, to the levitation for love in Baron Munchausen. I haven't seen
Fisher King in so long that I just flat out don't recall anything save the
samurai hallucination. Perhaps Gilliam is a Tarkovskyite. One American
director who shows some influence from Tark (more than some really) is David
Fincher--not intellectually (unfortunately) but visually. I've always meant to
check this: but I know that Fincher began as a director of music videos for
Madonna--one video featured a rip-off (hommage) to both Stalker (the scene
with Monkey moving the glasses across the table was reporoduced) and
Nostalghia (a statue of the Madonna with birds flying out of her chest).
Unfortunately, I don't remember which song it was for. Fincher's mainstream
films also show (subtler) influences from Tark--the use of water imagery in
Se7en and the religious imagery in Alien 3. The Game, too, seems to have some
similarities to Stalker--though with some Hollywoodizing, to be sure.

I realize I haven't supported myself all that well in the last section. I'm
still thinking the issues through. It's also been awhile since I watched much
of Fincher's work.  

Seamus
  
