<x-rich>

<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

>Here's something I've always wanted to mention and just remembered to:
when

>Alexander's wife sits down, in grief, to watch the home burn down she
assumes

>a very interesting pose. She is beside a puddle with her legs to one
side and

>leaning on her elbow (something like that). I remember seeing The
Sacrifice in

>the theatre with a friend--it was the first time either of us had seen
the

>film since going to see Nostalghia (twice in a row) a month or so
earlier. As

>we sat there, watching her laying there we both suddenly gasped. The
shot was

>a reversal (that is, shot from behind) of the final shot of Gorchakov
in

>Nostalghia as he assumes an identical pose (beside a puddle) facing
the

>audience, his home behind him. In Nostalghia, of course, the home has
(in a

>sense) been restored (via the death of the character). In The
Sacrifice the

>life of the character(s) is restored via the destruction of the house.
This

>seems to me to further link these two films in an interesting way . .
. but

>I'm still at a loss as to what the meaning might be.


</paraindent>Hey Tar you win my nomination for best Tark observation
for the month! This rocks the house. I hope I can follow this up with
some Sazen thoughts when I get back in town next week. 


Good oriental stuff, guys.


S

</x-rich>
