<x-rich>Hey Reichart


Thanks for the response. I'm really rushed so I can't promise I'm good
for much as I'm leaving town this afternoon. 


<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>>"...the problem of
dealing with the bazillion technical distractions -- " The more
technically proficient you are the less of the need to concentrate on
such matters and the more you can delve and focus on what is at the
heart of your aesthetic search...

</paraindent>

Well said. Or as John Mclaughlin once told Robert Frip: "One must learn
, learn, learn... then forget it all." Second nature helps sometimes.

<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

>the muse is like the "Prom Queen who casts a glance our way if she
sees fit." But only a few of us will have the courage and ability to
ask her to dance, and succeed; and fewer still, at the end of the night
when the festivities are over, will be able to take her to a hotel (in
the back of a car; home; forest; alleyway; wherever...) and bang the
hell outta her.

</paraindent>

You do have a way with words!

<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

> Also, as we all know, Tarkovksy was operating from a very specific
aesthetic ideology and infused all his decisions, whether planned
months ago or at a moments notice, with his prejudiced convictions.

</paraindent>

I don't think <italic>ideology</italic>  is the word I'd use but I
don't disagree. It's interesting in the doc when he mutters "we have to
make a cecicsion based on principle" Clearly he is falling back on some
preconception.


<paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

</paraindent><paraindent><param>right,right,right,left,left,left</param>>>
It's sort of a religious idea but wasn't it nice when we used to know
that the stars corresponded to the body, that we were at home in the
universe?

</paraindent><paraindent><param>right,right,left,left</param>

>"...used to know..."???  We are all carbon based beings; we carry the
origins of the stars inside of us. We are the universe.

</paraindent>

If that's how you<italic> feel</italic>  then we have no argument. You
are a better man than I. I know what you say as a fact but I feel too
much frailty for it to have any grounding. That doesn't mean I wouldn't
try to rise to the occasion in the alley behind the dance hall...
though I'd probably pull an Onan on her. 


BTW,  may I be forward enough to ask if you were simply being
rhetorical or if you've ever really ravaged a muse so thoroughly? What
was it like?



I've found T and his films to be an amazing compounding of oppositions.
 He seemed sometimes to go out of his way to insure contradiction and
paradox. You and I are just orienting our perspectives in two views
that may seem exclusive but both are important in their respective
contexts, I think. These are delicate points and sometimes have to be
articulated somehow to help give them a place in our day.  


I'm not sure what T would want us to learn most by studying his work.
Maybe to make us better observers of our own lives, I guess. I will
never hear a table saw again without thinking of <italic>Nostalghia.
</italic> Frailty and fear that I might cut off a finger makes it
imperative to watch closely, to move slowly, carefully... I don't want
to miss the point. 


Wish I had more time Rich, hope to hear from you when I return. 


No hay caminos, hay que caminar.


S


</x-rich>
