Pablo, you write:

<< Yes, also Galipoli (another Aussie film)thoroughly debunks any romantic 
 notions about WWI.
  >>

Yes, Gallipoli is a great example and brings up the First World War--one war
that, somehow, was not as glamorized when it was over as others. True, the
silent film era has an number jingoistic films--especially from Hollywood. But
All Quiet on the Western Front seemed to quickly eliminate the ability for
such films to succeed without being seen for tripe. Another excellent film
(similar, thematically, to Breaker Morant) is Kubrick's second film, Paths of
Glory--not only is it not glamorous, it is bitingly cynical. Since then, most
portrayals of the First World War have been (to varying degrees) condmenations
of war and brutality. Often it is used as a backdrop-- as in The English
Patient, or the very funny and sweet King of Hearts. The latter film was more
or less using it as a metaphor for Vietnam. For those who haven't seen it, I
recommend it highly: a soldier during WWI is the first to come across a small
town, not realizing that  the only people who have not evacuated are inmates
of the town asylum.

Enough rambling for now.

Seamus   
